{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915666866,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_05ujyxe0U5NIm8opGUWYbt0t","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Skill Reference File Templates\n3: description: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"skill reference templates\"\n6:   - \"reference file structure\"\n7:   - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n8:   - \"reference creation guidelines\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.8.0.16\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n15: \n16: Templates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Location & Naming\n23: \n24: **Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/references/`\n25: \n26: **Naming Convention:** snake_case with `.md` extension only\n27: \n28: | ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n29: |---------------|-----------------|\n30: | `implementation_workflows.md` | `ImplementationWorkflows.md` (PascalCase) |\n31: | `tool_catalog.md` | `tool-catalog.md` (kebab-case) |\n32: | `debugging_guide.md` | `DebuggingGuide.MD` (wrong case) |\n33: | `quick_reference.md` | `quickReference.md` (camelCase) |\n34: | `code_quality_standards.md` | `code quality standards.md` (spaces) |\n35: \n36: ### When to Create References\n37: \n38: **Create a reference file when:**\n39: - Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n40: - Decision trees with multiple branches\n41: - Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n42: - Systematic debugging procedures\n43: - Tool integration details\n44: - Content exceeds 200 lines\n45: \n46: **Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n47: - Content under 200 lines\n48: - Simple workflows (3-5 steps)\n49: - Overview and \"When to Use\" sections\n50: - Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n51: \n52: ---\n53: \n54: ## 2. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n55: \n56: ### Document Structure: Title and Intro\n57: \n58: **CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n59: \n60: ```markdown\n61: ---\n62: title: [Title]\n63: description: [One-line description - same as intro]\n64: trigger_phrases:\n65:   - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n66:   - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n67:   - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\n68: importance_tier: normal\n69: contextType: general\n70: version: 1.0.0.0\n71: ---\n72: \n73: # [Title]\n74: \n75: [1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n80: [All detailed content goes here, NOT in the intro]\n81: \n82: ```\n83: \n84: Every reference file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`, `important` only for formal contract docs; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n85: \n86: > **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and Section 1.**\n87: > The intro is a hook; Section 1 provides the details.\n88: \n89: #### GOOD Intro Structure\n90: \n91: ```markdown\n92: # Git Commit Workflows\n93: \n94: Step-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n95: \n96: ---\n97: \n98: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n99: \n100: ### Purpose\n101: Provides systematic workflows for analyzing changes, filtering artifacts, and creating well-structured commits.\n102: \n103: ### When to Use\n104: - Creating commits with multiple file changes\n105: - Filtering generated files from commits\n106: - Writing clear commit messages\n107: \n108: ### Core Principle\n109: Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n110: ```\n111: \n112: #### BAD Intro Structure (duplicates content)\n113: \n114: ```markdown\n115: # Git Commit Workflows\n116: \n117: Step-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n118: \n119: ### Core Principle   ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\n120: Atomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n121: \n122: ### When to Use      ← WRONG: This belongs in Section 1!\n123: - Creating commits with multiple file changes\n124: \n125: ---\n126: \n127: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n128: \n129: ### Purpose\n130: Provides systematic workflows...  ← Now this duplicates the intro!\n131: \n132: ### Core Principle\n133: Atomic commits...  ← DUPLICATED from intro!\n134: ```\n135: \n136: #### Intro vs Section 1 Content Placement\n137: \n138: | Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | Section 1 OVERVIEW |\n139: | --------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n140: | 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat) |\n141: | Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n142: | When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n143: | Primary Sources       | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (as \"Key Sources\") |\n144: | Purpose (detailed)    | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n145: | Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n146: | Any H3 subsections    | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES              |\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ### What Are AI Agent Skill Reference Files?\n151: \n152: Reference files are detailed technical documentation in the `references/` directory that provide deep-dive guidance with **explicit reasoning** - making thought processes visible, showing decision logic, and analyzing root causes.\n153: \n154: **Core Purpose**:\n155: - **Technical depth** - Step-by-step reasoning with rationale\n156: - **Phased workflows** - Structured processes with validation checkpoints\n157: - **Pattern libraries** - Before/after examples, comparison tables\n158: - **Tool integration** - MCP tools, scripts, asset references\n159: - **Root cause analysis** - Systematic debugging and troubleshooting\n160: \n161: **Key Difference from Generic Documentation**:\n162: - AI agent skills = Actionable workflows with explicit reasoning\n163: - Generic docs = Information reference without decision logic\n164: \n165: ### Progressive Disclosure in Skills\n166: \n167: ```\n168: Level 1: Metadata (name + description)\n169:          └─ Always in context (~100 words)\n170:             ↓\n171: Level 2: SKILL.md body\n172:          └─ When skill triggers (<5k words)\n173:             ↓\n174: Level 3: Reference files (this document)\n175:          └─ Loaded as needed (500-3000 lines per file)\n176: ```\n177: \n178: **Reference files = Level 3**: Deep technical guidance loaded only when the agent needs specific workflow details.\n179: \n180: ---\n181: \n182: ## 3. WHEN TO CREATE REFERENCE FILES\n183: \n184: ### Create Reference File When\n185: \n186: **Workflow Complexity**:\n187: - Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n188: - Decision trees with multiple branches\n189: - Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n190: - Systematic debugging procedures\n191: \n192: **Technical Depth**:\n193: - Root cause analysis required\n194: - Tool integration details (MCP, scripts)\n195: - Before/after code transformations\n196: - Common error patterns and fixes\n197: \n198: **Size Threshold**:\n199: - Content exceeds 200 lines\n200: - Multiple related workflows\n201: - Extensive troubleshooting needed\n202: \n203: ### Keep in SKILL.md When\n204: \n205: **Core Content**:\n206: - Overview and \"When to Use\"\n207: - High-level workflow (3-5 steps)\n208: - Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n209:   > **Note**: RULES sections in SKILL.md use ALL-CAPS H3 headers: `### ALWAYS`, `### NEVER`, `### ESCALATE IF` (or `####` at phase depth). See [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) for the complete pattern.\n210: - Quick reference\n211: \n212: **Size**: Content under 200 lines\n213: \n214: ### Reference File Types for AI Agent Skills\n215: \n216: | Type                | Purpose                                | Example (snake_case)          | Size           |\n217: | ------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | -------------- |\n218: | **Workflow**        | Multi-phase processes with checkpoints | `implementation_workflows.md` | 500-1500 lines |\n219: | **Pattern Library** | Code patterns with before/after        | `shared_patterns.md`          | 300-800 lines  |\n220: | **Standards**       | Rules and conventions                  | `code_quality_standards.md`   | 400-1000 lines |\n\n(Showing lines 1-220 of 1025. Use offset=221 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Skill Reference File Templates\ndescription: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill reference templates\"\n  - \"reference file structure\"\n  - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n  - \"reference creation guidelines\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.16\n---\n\n# Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n\nTemplates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Skill Reference File Templates\ndescription: Comprehensive templates for creating effective reference files for AI agent skills with workflows, decision logic, and validation checkpoints.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill reference templates\"\n  - \"reference file structure\"\n  - \"explicit reasoning references\"\n  - \"reference creation guidelines\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.16\n---\n\n# Skill Reference File Templates - AI Agent Skills\n\nTemplates for creating reference files in AI agent skills with deep-dive technical guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming\n\n**Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/references/`\n\n**Naming Convention:** snake_case with `.md` extension only\n\n| ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n|---------------|-----------------|\n| `implementation_workflows.md` | `ImplementationWorkflows.md` (PascalCase) |\n| `tool_catalog.md` | `tool-catalog.md` (kebab-case) |\n| `debugging_guide.md` | `DebuggingGuide.MD` (wrong case) |\n| `quick_reference.md` | `quickReference.md` (camelCase) |\n| `code_quality_standards.md` | `code quality standards.md` (spaces) |\n\n### When to Create References\n\n**Create a reference file when:**\n- Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n- Decision trees with multiple branches\n- Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n- Systematic debugging procedures\n- Tool integration details\n- Content exceeds 200 lines\n\n**Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n- Content under 200 lines\n- Simple workflows (3-5 steps)\n- Overview and \"When to Use\" sections\n- Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n\n---\n\n## 2. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n\n### Document Structure: Title and Intro\n\n**CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n\n```markdown\n---\ntitle: [Title]\ndescription: [One-line description - same as intro]\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# [Title]\n\n[1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n[All detailed content goes here, NOT in the intro]\n\n```\n\nEvery reference file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`, `important` only for formal contract docs; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n\n> **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and Section 1.**\n> The intro is a hook; Section 1 provides the details.\n\n#### GOOD Intro Structure\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Workflows\n\nStep-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nProvides systematic workflows for analyzing changes, filtering artifacts, and creating well-structured commits.\n\n### When to Use\n- Creating commits with multiple file changes\n- Filtering generated files from commits\n- Writing clear commit messages\n\n### Core Principle\nAtomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n```\n\n#### BAD Intro Structure (duplicates content)\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Workflows\n\nStep-by-step workflows for creating clean, atomic commits with proper filtering.\n\n### Core Principle   ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\nAtomic commits with clear intent + filtered artifacts = maintainable Git history.\n\n### When to Use      ← WRONG: This belongs in Section 1!\n- Creating commits with multiple file changes\n\n---\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nProvides systematic workflows...  ← Now this duplicates the intro!\n\n### Core Principle\nAtomic commits...  ← DUPLICATED from intro!\n```\n\n#### Intro vs Section 1 Content Placement\n\n| Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | Section 1 OVERVIEW |\n| --------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------ |\n| 1-2 sentence summary  | ✅ YES            | ❌ NO (don't repeat) |\n| Core Principle        | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| When to Use           | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Primary Sources       | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES (as \"Key Sources\") |\n| Purpose (detailed)    | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Prerequisites         | ❌ NO             | ✅ YES              |\n| Any H3 subsections    | ❌ NEVER          | ✅ YES              |\n\n---\n\n### What Are AI Agent Skill Reference Files?\n\nReference files are detailed technical documentation in the `references/` directory that provide deep-dive guidance with **explicit reasoning** - making thought processes visible, showing decision logic, and analyzing root causes.\n\n**Core Purpose**:\n- **Technical depth** - Step-by-step reasoning with rationale\n- **Phased workflows** - Structured processes with validation checkpoints\n- **Pattern libraries** - Before/after examples, comparison tables\n- **Tool integration** - MCP tools, scripts, asset references\n- **Root cause analysis** - Systematic debugging and troubleshooting\n\n**Key Difference from Generic Documentation**:\n- AI agent skills = Actionable workflows with explicit reasoning\n- Generic docs = Information reference without decision logic\n\n### Progressive Disclosure in Skills\n\n```\nLevel 1: Metadata (name + description)\n         └─ Always in context (~100 words)\n            ↓\nLevel 2: SKILL.md body\n         └─ When skill triggers (<5k words)\n            ↓\nLevel 3: Reference files (this document)\n         └─ Loaded as needed (500-3000 lines per file)\n```\n\n**Reference files = Level 3**: Deep technical guidance loaded only when the agent needs specific workflow details.\n\n---\n\n## 3. WHEN TO CREATE REFERENCE FILES\n\n### Create Reference File When\n\n**Workflow Complexity**:\n- Multi-phase workflows with validation checkpoints\n- Decision trees with multiple branches\n- Pattern libraries with 5+ variations\n- Systematic debugging procedures\n\n**Technical Depth**:\n- Root cause analysis required\n- Tool integration details (MCP, scripts)\n- Before/after code transformations\n- Common error patterns and fixes\n\n**Size Threshold**:\n- Content exceeds 200 lines\n- Multiple related workflows\n- Extensive troubleshooting needed\n\n### Keep in SKILL.md When\n\n**Core Content**:\n- Overview and \"When to Use\"\n- High-level workflow (3-5 steps)\n- Essential rules (ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF)\n  > **Note**: RULES sections in SKILL.md use ALL-CAPS H3 headers: `### ALWAYS`, `### NEVER`, `### ESCALATE IF` (or `####` at phase depth). See [skill_md_template.md](./skill_md_template.md) for the complete pattern.\n- Quick reference\n\n**Size**: Content under 200 lines\n\n### Reference File Types for AI Agent Skills\n\n| Type                | Purpose                                | Example (snake_case)          | Size           |\n| ------------------- | -------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- | -------------- |\n| **Workflow**        | Multi-phase processes with checkpoints | `implementation_workflows.md` | 500-1500 lines |\n| **Pattern Library** | Code patterns with before/after        | `shared_patterns.md`          | 300-800 lines  |\n| **Standards**       | Rules and conventions                  | `code_quality_standards.md`   | 400-1000 lines |","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":220,"totalLines":1025,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_reference_template.md","time":{"start":1783915666859,"end":1783915666864}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d074688ef23ef0016a546492c7848191b965707ba7f28044"}},"id":"prt_f59a8dd7e001miscKMPdE6ZoBZ","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a8967f0016hU7NQSPitq0xc"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915666879,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_aA9wqzKcGjECQ5pCxargwoXb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Skill Asset File Templates\n3: description: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"skill asset templates\"\n6:   - \"asset file guidelines\"\n7:   - \"asset document structure\"\n8:   - \"standard asset structure\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.8.0.19\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Skill Asset File Templates - Creation Guidelines\n15: \n16: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n17: \n18: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n19: \n20: ### Location & Naming\n21: \n22: **Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/assets/`\n23: \n24: **Naming Convention:** snake_case with appropriate extension\n25: \n26: | ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n27: |---------------|-----------------|\n28: | `frontmatter_templates.md` | `FrontmatterTemplates.md` (PascalCase) |\n29: | `config_examples.yaml` | `config-examples.yaml` (kebab-case) |\n30: | `validation_checklist.md` | `ValidationChecklist.MD` (wrong case) |\n31: | `emoji_reference.md` | `emojiReference.md` (camelCase) |\n32: \n33: ### When to Create Assets\n34: \n35: **Create an asset file when:**\n36: - Templates users apply repeatedly\n37: - Reference data >50 lines and self-contained\n38: - Multiple examples of same pattern exist\n39: - Lookup tables or decision matrices needed\n40: - Template variations for different scenarios\n41: \n42: **Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n43: - Content <30 lines\n44: - Tightly coupled to workflow logic\n45: - Needs to be visible immediately (not progressive disclosure)\n46: - Part of core instructions (RULES, WORKFLOW sections)\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 2. ASSET FILE TYPES\n51: \n52: ### Template Files\n53: **Purpose**: Provide copy-paste starting points for common tasks\n54: \n55: **Naming**: `[content-type]_templates.md`\n56: - Example: `frontmatter_templates.md`, `structure_templates.md`\n57: \n58: **Structure**:\n59: - One template per section\n60: - Include field descriptions\n61: - Show complete examples\n62: - Explain when to use each template\n63: \n64: **Use cases**:\n65: - Document templates (SKILL.md, commands, knowledge files)\n66: - Configuration templates (YAML, JSON)\n67: - Code templates (functions, classes, modules)\n68: \n69: ### Reference Files\n70: **Purpose**: Provide lookup tables, decision trees, or reference data\n71: \n72: **Naming**: `[topic]_reference.md`\n73: - Example: `emoji_reference.md`, `validation_reference.md`\n74: \n75: **Structure**:\n76: - Tables or lists for quick lookup\n77: - Decision matrices\n78: - Classification systems\n79: - Standards and conventions\n80: \n81: **Use cases**:\n82: - Emoji selection guides\n83: - File type classifications\n84: - Validation rule sets\n85: - Naming conventions\n86: \n87: ### Example Files\n88: **Purpose**: Show working examples of skill outputs\n89: \n90: **Naming**: `[topic]_examples.md`\n91: - Example: `optimization_examples.md`, `skill_examples.md`\n92: \n93: **Structure**:\n94: - Before/after comparisons\n95: - Annotated examples\n96: - Multiple variations\n97: - Anti-patterns to avoid\n98: \n99: **Use cases**:\n100: - Complete skill applications\n101: - Common patterns\n102: - Edge cases\n103: - Quality standards\n104: \n105: ### Guide Files\n106: **Purpose**: Detailed how-to guides for complex processes\n107: \n108: **Naming**: `[process]_guide.md`\n109: - Example: `packaging_guide.md`, `distribution_guide.md`\n110: \n111: **Structure**:\n112: - Step-by-step instructions\n113: - Troubleshooting sections\n114: - Best practices\n115: - Common pitfalls\n116: \n117: **Use cases**:\n118: - Multi-step processes\n119: - Advanced techniques\n120: - Workflow deep-dives\n121: - Integration guides\n122: \n123: ---\n124: \n125: ## 3. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n126: \n127: ### Title and Intro\n128: \n129: **CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n130: \n131: ```markdown\n132: ---\n133: title: [Title]\n134: description: [One-line description - same as intro]\n135: trigger_phrases:\n136:   - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n137:   - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n138:   - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\n139: importance_tier: normal\n140: contextType: general\n141: version: 1.0.0.0\n142: ---\n143: \n144: # [Title]\n145: \n146: [1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n147: \n148: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n149: \n150: ### Purpose\n151: \n152: [Why this asset exists]\n153: \n154: ### Usage\n155: \n156: [How to use this asset - copy instructions, customization notes]\n157: \n158: ---\n159: \n160: \\## 2. [Content Section]\n161: \n162: [The actual template/checklist/snippet content]\n163: \n164: ---\n165: \n166: ## N. Related Resources (optional, if present must be last)\n167: \n168: [Links to related files]\n169: \n170: ```\n171: \n172: Every asset file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n173: \n174: > **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and OVERVIEW section.**\n175: > The intro is a hook; OVERVIEW provides the details.\n176: \n177: #### GOOD Intro Structure\n178: \n179: ```markdown\n180: # Git Commit Templates\n181: \n182: Copy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n183: \n184: \\## 1. OVERVIEW\n185: \n186: ### Purpose\n187: \n188: Provides consistent commit message formats for atomic commits...\n189: \n190: ### Usage\n191: \n192: Copy the appropriate template based on commit type...\n193: \n194: ---\n195: \n196: \\## 2. COMMIT TEMPLATES\n197: ...\n198: ```\n199: \n200: #### BAD Intro Structure (too long, has subsections)\n201: \n202: ```markdown\n203: # Git Commit Templates\n204: \n205: Copy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n206: \n207: ### Core Principle    ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\n208: Atomic commits with clear intent = maintainable history.\n209: \n210: ### When to Use       ← WRONG: This belongs in OVERVIEW section!\n211: - Creating new features\n212: - Fixing bugs\n213: \n214: ---\n215: ```\n216: \n217: ### Intro vs OVERVIEW Content Placement\n218: \n219: | Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | OVERVIEW Section       |\n220: | --------------------- | ---------------- | ---------------------- |\n\n(Showing lines 1-220 of 946. Use offset=221 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Skill Asset File Templates\ndescription: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill asset templates\"\n  - \"asset file guidelines\"\n  - \"asset document structure\"\n  - \"standard asset structure\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.19\n---\n\n# Skill Asset File Templates - Creation Guidelines\n\nTemplates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Skill Asset File Templates\ndescription: Templates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill asset templates\"\n  - \"asset file guidelines\"\n  - \"asset document structure\"\n  - \"standard asset structure\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.19\n---\n\n# Skill Asset File Templates - Creation Guidelines\n\nTemplates and guidelines for creating asset files in AI agent skills.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Location & Naming\n\n**Location:** `.opencode/skills/[skill-name]/assets/`\n\n**Naming Convention:** snake_case with appropriate extension\n\n| ✅ Valid Names | ❌ Invalid Names |\n|---------------|-----------------|\n| `frontmatter_templates.md` | `FrontmatterTemplates.md` (PascalCase) |\n| `config_examples.yaml` | `config-examples.yaml` (kebab-case) |\n| `validation_checklist.md` | `ValidationChecklist.MD` (wrong case) |\n| `emoji_reference.md` | `emojiReference.md` (camelCase) |\n\n### When to Create Assets\n\n**Create an asset file when:**\n- Templates users apply repeatedly\n- Reference data >50 lines and self-contained\n- Multiple examples of same pattern exist\n- Lookup tables or decision matrices needed\n- Template variations for different scenarios\n\n**Keep in SKILL.md when:**\n- Content <30 lines\n- Tightly coupled to workflow logic\n- Needs to be visible immediately (not progressive disclosure)\n- Part of core instructions (RULES, WORKFLOW sections)\n\n---\n\n## 2. ASSET FILE TYPES\n\n### Template Files\n**Purpose**: Provide copy-paste starting points for common tasks\n\n**Naming**: `[content-type]_templates.md`\n- Example: `frontmatter_templates.md`, `structure_templates.md`\n\n**Structure**:\n- One template per section\n- Include field descriptions\n- Show complete examples\n- Explain when to use each template\n\n**Use cases**:\n- Document templates (SKILL.md, commands, knowledge files)\n- Configuration templates (YAML, JSON)\n- Code templates (functions, classes, modules)\n\n### Reference Files\n**Purpose**: Provide lookup tables, decision trees, or reference data\n\n**Naming**: `[topic]_reference.md`\n- Example: `emoji_reference.md`, `validation_reference.md`\n\n**Structure**:\n- Tables or lists for quick lookup\n- Decision matrices\n- Classification systems\n- Standards and conventions\n\n**Use cases**:\n- Emoji selection guides\n- File type classifications\n- Validation rule sets\n- Naming conventions\n\n### Example Files\n**Purpose**: Show working examples of skill outputs\n\n**Naming**: `[topic]_examples.md`\n- Example: `optimization_examples.md`, `skill_examples.md`\n\n**Structure**:\n- Before/after comparisons\n- Annotated examples\n- Multiple variations\n- Anti-patterns to avoid\n\n**Use cases**:\n- Complete skill applications\n- Common patterns\n- Edge cases\n- Quality standards\n\n### Guide Files\n**Purpose**: Detailed how-to guides for complex processes\n\n**Naming**: `[process]_guide.md`\n- Example: `packaging_guide.md`, `distribution_guide.md`\n\n**Structure**:\n- Step-by-step instructions\n- Troubleshooting sections\n- Best practices\n- Common pitfalls\n\n**Use cases**:\n- Multi-step processes\n- Advanced techniques\n- Workflow deep-dives\n- Integration guides\n\n---\n\n## 3. DOCUMENT STRUCTURE\n\n### Title and Intro\n\n**CRITICAL: The intro after the H1 title must be 1-2 SHORT sentences only.**\n\n```markdown\n---\ntitle: [Title]\ndescription: [One-line description - same as intro]\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"[distinctive phrase one]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase two]\"\n  - \"[distinctive phrase three]\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# [Title]\n\n[1-2 SHORT sentences only. Brief hook/summary. NO subsections, NO headers here.]\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\n[Why this asset exists]\n\n### Usage\n\n[How to use this asset - copy instructions, customization notes]\n\n---\n\n\\## 2. [Content Section]\n\n[The actual template/checklist/snippet content]\n\n---\n\n## N. Related Resources (optional, if present must be last)\n\n[Links to related files]\n\n```\n\nEvery asset file carries this full 5-field frontmatter block: the Skill Advisor harvests it as routing signal (3-8 lowercase multi-word `trigger_phrases` drawn from the doc's content; `importance_tier` defaults to `normal`; `contextType` one of `planning|research|implementation|general`). See [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for field rules.\n\n> **WARNING: DO NOT duplicate content between intro and OVERVIEW section.**\n> The intro is a hook; OVERVIEW provides the details.\n\n#### GOOD Intro Structure\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Templates\n\nCopy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n\n\\## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nProvides consistent commit message formats for atomic commits...\n\n### Usage\n\nCopy the appropriate template based on commit type...\n\n---\n\n\\## 2. COMMIT TEMPLATES\n...\n```\n\n#### BAD Intro Structure (too long, has subsections)\n\n```markdown\n# Git Commit Templates\n\nCopy-paste templates for creating well-structured commit messages.\n\n### Core Principle    ← WRONG: No headers in intro!\nAtomic commits with clear intent = maintainable history.\n\n### When to Use       ← WRONG: This belongs in OVERVIEW section!\n- Creating new features\n- Fixing bugs\n\n---\n```\n\n### Intro vs OVERVIEW Content Placement\n\n| Content Type          | Intro (after H1) | OVERVIEW Section       |\n| --------------------- | ---------------- | ---------------------- |","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":220,"totalLines":946,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/assets/skill/skill_asset_template.md","time":{"start":1783915666874,"end":1783915666878}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d074688ef23ef0016a546492c7a48191895d0aba977f134a"}},"id":"prt_f59a8ddad0012Gg4LudIiVUBBd","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a8967f0016hU7NQSPitq0xc"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915666926,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_bsdOsoBNwmExHRNb7kPSt0EQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py","offset":1,"limit":500},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: #!/usr/bin/env python3\n2: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n3: # COMPONENT: README/DOCUMENTATION FORMAT VALIDATOR\n4: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n5: \n6: \"\"\"\n7: README/Documentation Format Validator\n8: \n9: Validates markdown documentation against template rules to ensure\n10: consistent formatting with proper TOC, H2 emojis, and section structure.\n11: \n12: Usage:\n13:     python validate_document.py <document.md> [--type readme|skill|reference|asset|agent|command|install_guide|spec|changelog]\n14:     python validate_document.py <document.md> --json\n15:     python validate_document.py <document.md> --fix [--dry-run]\n16:     python validate_document.py <document.md> --blocking-only\n17: \n18: Exit Codes:\n19:     0 - Valid (no blocking errors)\n20:     1 - Invalid (blocking errors found)\n21:     2 - File not found or parse error\n22: \n23: Examples:\n24:     python validate_document.py README.md\n25:     python validate_document.py SKILL.md --type skill\n26:     python validate_document.py doc.md --json\n27:     python validate_document.py doc.md --fix --dry-run\n28: \"\"\"\n29: \n30: import argparse\n31: import json\n32: import re\n33: import sys\n34: from pathlib import Path\n35: from typing import Any, Dict, List, Optional, Tuple\n36: \n37: \n38: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n39: # 1. CONFIGURATION\n40: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n41: \n42: EMOJI_PATTERN = re.compile(\n43:     \"[\"\n44:     \"\\U0001F300-\\U0001F9FF\"\n45:     \"\\U00002600-\\U000026FF\"\n46:     \"\\U00002700-\\U000027BF\"\n47:     \"\\U0001F600-\\U0001F64F\"\n48:     \"\\U0001F680-\\U0001F6FF\"\n49:     \"\\U0001F1E0-\\U0001F1FF\"\n50:     \"]\"\n51: )\n52: \n53: # Paths to exclude from validation (auto-generated, third-party, etc.)\n54: EXCLUDED_PATH_PATTERNS = [\n55:     '.pytest_cache',\n56:     'node_modules',\n57:     '__pycache__',\n58:     '.git',\n59:     'vendor',\n60:     'dist',\n61:     'build',\n62:     '.venv',\n63:     'venv',\n64: ]\n65: \n66: # Third-party directories that use different README conventions\n67: THIRD_PARTY_PATTERNS = [\n68:     # Add third-party patterns here if needed\n69: ]\n70: \n71: # Template directories with intentionally minimal placeholder READMEs\n72: TEMPLATE_PATTERNS = [\n73:     'system-spec-kit/templates/',  # Spec folder templates are minimal by design\n74: ]\n75: \n76: \n77: def should_exclude_path(file_path: str) -> Tuple[bool, Optional[str]]:\n78:     \"\"\"Check if file path should be excluded from validation.\"\"\"\n79:     path_str = str(file_path)\n80: \n81:     # Check excluded patterns (auto-generated, dependencies)\n82:     for pattern in EXCLUDED_PATH_PATTERNS:\n83:         if f'/{pattern}/' in path_str or f'\\\\{pattern}\\\\' in path_str:\n84:             return True, f\"Excluded: matches pattern '{pattern}'\"\n85: \n86:     # Check third-party patterns\n87:     for pattern in THIRD_PARTY_PATTERNS:\n88:         if pattern in path_str:\n89:             return True, f\"Third-party: matches pattern '{pattern}'\"\n90: \n91:     # Check template patterns (intentionally minimal)\n92:     for pattern in TEMPLATE_PATTERNS:\n93:         if pattern in path_str:\n94:             return True, f\"Template: matches pattern '{pattern}' (intentionally minimal)\"\n95: \n96:     return False, None\n97: \n98: \n99: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n100: # 2. UTILITIES\n101: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n102: \n103: def load_template_rules(script_dir: Path) -> Dict[str, Any]:\n104:     \"\"\"Load template_rules.json from assets folder.\"\"\"\n105:     rules_path = script_dir.parent / \"assets\" / \"template_rules.json\"\n106:     if not rules_path.exists():\n107:         print(f\"Error: template_rules.json not found at {rules_path}\", file=sys.stderr)\n108:         sys.exit(2)\n109: \n110:     with open(rules_path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n111:         return json.load(f)\n112: \n113: \n114: def load_rules() -> Dict[str, Any]:\n115:     \"\"\"Load template rules for callers importing the validator module.\"\"\"\n116:     return load_template_rules(Path(__file__).parent)\n117: \n118: \n119: def detect_document_type(file_path: str, content: str, rules: Dict[str, Any]) -> str:\n120:     \"\"\"Detect document type from file path or content.\"\"\"\n121:     path_lower = str(file_path).lower()\n122: \n123:     if '/manual_testing_playbook/' in path_lower or '\\\\manual_testing_playbook\\\\' in path_lower:\n124:         # A per-feature playbook leaf sits one level below the category root\n125:         # (manual_testing_playbook/<category>/<feature>.md). Classify by that structural\n126:         # position rather than an ordinal folder-name prefix, so category folders can be\n127:         # named by meaning alone. The root index file (whose parent IS the\n128:         # manual_testing_playbook dir) is intentionally excluded.\n129:         if Path(path_lower).parent.parent.name == 'manual_testing_playbook':\n130:             return 'playbook_feature'\n131:     # Per-feature catalog leaves sit one level below the catalog root\n132:     # (feature_catalog/<category>/<feature>.md). These carry the Validation And Tests\n133:     # table whose Type taxonomy and placeholder rows the generic readme path misses.\n134:     # Classify by structural position rather than an ordinal folder-name prefix; the\n135:     # root index file (whose parent IS the feature_catalog dir) stays excluded.\n136:     if '/feature_catalog/' in path_lower or '\\\\feature_catalog\\\\' in path_lower:\n137:         if Path(path_lower).parent.parent.name == 'feature_catalog':\n138:             return 'feature_catalog'\n139:     if '/command/' in path_lower or '\\\\command\\\\' in path_lower or '/commands/' in path_lower or '\\\\commands\\\\' in path_lower:\n140:         return 'command'\n141:     if '/install_guides/' in path_lower or '\\\\install_guides\\\\' in path_lower:\n142:         return 'install_guide'\n143:     if 'install_guide' in Path(path_lower).stem:\n144:         return 'install_guide'\n145:     # Changelog files: under .opencode/changelog/, .opencode/skills/*/changelog/,\n146:     # or spec-folder nested changelog/ subdirectories. Files match v{VERSION}.md or changelog-*.md\n147:     if '/changelog/' in path_lower or '\\\\changelog\\\\' in path_lower:\n148:         return 'changelog'\n149:     if path_lower.endswith('readme.md'):\n150:         return 'readme'\n151:     if path_lower.endswith('skill.md'):\n152:         return 'skill'\n153:     if '/specs/' in path_lower or '\\\\specs\\\\' in path_lower:\n154:         return 'spec'\n155:     if '/agents/' in path_lower or '\\\\agents\\\\' in path_lower or '/agent/' in path_lower or '\\\\agent\\\\' in path_lower:\n156:         return 'agent'\n157:     if '/references/' in path_lower or '\\\\references\\\\' in path_lower:\n158:         return 'reference'\n159:     if '/assets/' in path_lower or '\\\\assets\\\\' in path_lower:\n160:         return 'asset'\n161: \n162:     # Default to readme for general markdown\n163:     return 'readme'\n164: \n165: \n166: def has_emoji(text: str) -> bool:\n167:     \"\"\"Check if text contains an emoji.\"\"\"\n168:     return bool(EMOJI_PATTERN.search(text))\n169: \n170: \n171: def extract_first_emoji(text: str) -> Optional[str]:\n172:     \"\"\"Extract the first emoji from text.\"\"\"\n173:     match = EMOJI_PATTERN.search(text)\n174:     return match.group(0) if match else None\n175: \n176: \n177: def normalize_section_name(name: str) -> str:\n178:     \"\"\"Normalize section name for lookup in rules.\"\"\"\n179:     name = EMOJI_PATTERN.sub('', name)\n180:     name = name.strip().lower().replace(' ', '_')\n181:     name = re.sub(r'[^a-z0-9_]', '', name)\n182:     return name\n183: \n184: \n185: def extract_section_name_text(text: str) -> str:\n186:     \"\"\"\n187:     Extract the section name text after removing number prefix and emoji.\n188: \n189:     Examples:\n190:         \"1. 📖 Overview\" -> \"Overview\"\n191:         \"📖 OVERVIEW\" -> \"OVERVIEW\"\n192:         \"1. Overview\" -> \"Overview\"\n193:     \"\"\"\n194:     # Remove leading number and dot (e.g., \"1. \")\n195:     text = re.sub(r'^\\d+\\.\\s*', '', text)\n196:     # Remove emoji\n197:     text = EMOJI_PATTERN.sub('', text)\n198:     # Clean up whitespace\n199:     return text.strip()\n200: \n201: \n202: def is_uppercase_section(text: str) -> bool:\n203:     \"\"\"\n204:     Check if section name is ALL CAPS.\n205: \n206:     Handles special characters like &, ', -, etc.\n207:     Only checks alphabetic characters for case.\n208: \n209:     Examples:\n210:         \"OVERVIEW\" -> True\n211:         \"Overview\" -> False\n212:         \"INSTALLATION & SETUP\" -> True\n213:         \"WHAT'S NEXT?\" -> True\n214:         \"MCP TOOLS\" -> True\n215:     \"\"\"\n216:     section_name = extract_section_name_text(text)\n217:     # Check if all alphabetic characters are uppercase\n218:     alpha_chars = [c for c in section_name if c.isalpha()]\n219:     if not alpha_chars:\n220:         return True  # No alphabetic chars, consider valid\n221:     return all(c.isupper() for c in alpha_chars)\n222: \n223: \n224: def make_uppercase_section(text: str) -> str:\n225:     \"\"\"\n226:     Convert section name to ALL CAPS while preserving structure.\n227: \n228:     Examples:\n229:         \"Overview\" -> \"OVERVIEW\"\n230:         \"Quick Start\" -> \"QUICK START\"\n231:         \"What's Next?\" -> \"WHAT'S NEXT?\"\n232:     \"\"\"\n233:     return text.upper()\n234: \n235: \n236: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n237: # 3. TOC VALIDATION\n238: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n239: \n240: def validate_toc(content: str, doc_type_rules: Dict[str, Any], rules: Dict[str, Any]) -> List[Dict[str, Any]]:\n241:     \"\"\"Validate TABLE OF CONTENTS section.\"\"\"\n242:     errors = []\n243: \n244:     if not doc_type_rules.get('tocRequired', False):\n245:         return errors\n246: \n247:     # Accept variations with emoji (📑) or without\n248:     # Pattern: ## [optional emoji] TABLE OF CONTENTS\n249:     toc_match = re.search(\n250:         r'## (?:[^\\w\\s]\\s+)?TABLE OF CONTENTS\\s*\\n(.*?)(?=\\n---|\\n## |\\Z)',\n251:         content,\n252:         re.DOTALL | re.IGNORECASE\n253:     )\n254: \n255:     if not toc_match:\n256:         errors.append({\n257:             'type': 'missing_toc',\n258:             'severity': 'blocking',\n259:             'message': 'Missing TABLE OF CONTENTS section',\n260:             'fix_hint': 'Add \"## TABLE OF CONTENTS\" section with linked entries'\n261:         })\n262:         return errors\n263: \n264:     toc_content = toc_match.group(1)\n265: \n266:     for line_num, line in enumerate(toc_content.strip().split('\\n'), start=1):\n267:         line = line.strip()\n268:         if not line.startswith('- ['):\n269:             continue\n270: \n271:         # Double-dash anchors required for GitHub compatibility\n272:         anchor_match = re.search(r'\\(#(\\d+)-([a-z])', line)\n273:         if anchor_match:\n274:             errors.append({\n275:                 'type': 'toc_single_dash_anchor',\n276:                 'severity': 'blocking',\n277:                 'message': f'TOC anchor uses single dash instead of double dash',\n278:                 'line': line,\n279:                 'fix_hint': f'Change \"#N-\" to \"#N--\" in anchor',\n280:                 'auto_fixable': True,\n281:                 'fix': line.replace(f'#{anchor_match.group(1)}-', f'#{anchor_match.group(1)}--')\n282:             })\n283: \n284:         entry_match = re.search(r'\\[(.+?)\\]', line)\n285:         if entry_match:\n286:             entry_text = entry_match.group(1)\n287: \n288:             # Check for ALL CAPS (only for readme type which requires it)\n289:             uppercase_required = doc_type_rules.get('tocUppercaseRequired', False)\n290:             if uppercase_required and not is_uppercase_section(entry_text):\n291:                 section_text = extract_section_name_text(entry_text)\n292:                 # Build fixed entry: preserve number and emoji, uppercase the name\n293:                 # Pattern: \"N. EMOJI name\" -> \"N. EMOJI NAME\"\n294:                 fixed_entry = re.sub(\n295:                     r'^(\\d+\\.\\s*)([^\\w\\s]\\s*)?(.+)$',\n296:                     lambda m: f\"{m.group(1)}{m.group(2) or ''}{m.group(3).upper()}\",\n297:                     entry_text\n298:                 )\n299:                 fixed_line = line.replace(f'[{entry_text}]', f'[{fixed_entry}]')\n300: \n301:                 errors.append({\n302:                     'type': 'toc_not_uppercase',\n303:                     'severity': 'blocking',\n304:                     'message': f'TOC entry not ALL CAPS: \"{entry_text}\"',\n305:                     'line': line,\n306:                     'auto_fixable': True,\n307:                     'fix': fixed_line,\n308:                     'fix_hint': f'Change \"{section_text}\" to \"{section_text.upper()}\"'\n309:                 })\n310: \n311:     return errors\n312: \n313: \n314: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n315: # 4. HEADER VALIDATION\n316: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n317: \n318: def validate_h2_headers(content: str, doc_type_rules: Dict[str, Any], rules: Dict[str, Any]) -> List[Dict[str, Any]]:\n319:     \"\"\"Validate H2 header format and emojis.\"\"\"\n320:     errors = []\n321: \n322:     h2_pattern = re.compile(r'^## (\\d+)\\.\\s+(.+)$', re.MULTILINE)\n323:     matches = list(h2_pattern.finditer(content))\n324: \n325:     if not matches:\n326:         # No numbered H2 headers found - check if this is expected\n327:         # Some documents might use different header styles\n328:         return errors\n329: \n330:     expected_num = 1\n331:     emoji_required = doc_type_rules.get('h2EmojiRequired', True)\n332:     section_emojis = doc_type_rules.get('sectionEmojis', {})\n333:     section_aliases = doc_type_rules.get('sectionAliases', {})\n334: \n335:     for match in matches:\n336:         num = int(match.group(1))\n337:         title = match.group(2).strip()\n338:         line = match.group(0)\n339: \n340:         if num != expected_num:\n341:             errors.append({\n342:                 'type': 'non_sequential_numbering',\n343:                 'severity': 'warning',\n344:                 'message': f'Non-sequential section number: expected {expected_num}, found {num}',\n345:                 'line': line\n346:             })\n347:         expected_num = num + 1\n348: \n349:         if emoji_required:\n350:             title_has_emoji = has_emoji(title)\n351: \n352:             if not title_has_emoji:\n353:                 section_name = normalize_section_name(title)\n354: \n355:                 if section_name in section_aliases:\n356:                     section_name = section_aliases[section_name]\n357: \n358:                 expected_emoji = section_emojis.get(section_name)\n359: \n360:                 # Fallback: match ignoring underscores for flexibility\n361:                 if not expected_emoji:\n362:                     section_name_no_underscore = section_name.replace('_', '')\n363:                     for key, emoji in section_emojis.items():\n364:                         if key.replace('_', '') == section_name_no_underscore:\n365:                             expected_emoji = emoji\n366:                             break\n367: \n368:                 errors.append({\n369:                     'type': 'missing_h2_emoji',\n370:                     'severity': 'blocking',\n371:                     'message': f'H2 header missing emoji: \"{line}\"',\n372:                     'line': line,\n373:                     'section_name': section_name,\n374:                     'expected_emoji': expected_emoji,\n375:                     'auto_fixable': expected_emoji is not None,\n376:                     'fix': f'## {num}. {expected_emoji} {title}' if expected_emoji else None,\n377:                     'fix_hint': f'Add {expected_emoji} after \"{num}.\"' if expected_emoji else 'Add appropriate emoji after section number'\n378:                 })\n379: \n380:         # Check for ALL CAPS (only for document types that require it)\n381:         uppercase_required = doc_type_rules.get('h2UppercaseRequired', False)\n382:         if uppercase_required and not is_uppercase_section(title):\n383:             section_text = extract_section_name_text(title)\n384:             # Extract emoji if present\n385:             emoji = extract_first_emoji(title)\n386: \n387:             if emoji:\n388:                 # Has emoji: \"EMOJI name\" -> \"EMOJI NAME\"\n389:                 title_after_emoji = EMOJI_PATTERN.sub('', title).strip()\n390:                 fixed_title = f'{emoji} {title_after_emoji.upper()}'\n391:             else:\n392:                 # No emoji: just uppercase\n393:                 fixed_title = title.upper()\n394: \n395:             errors.append({\n396:                 'type': 'h2_not_uppercase',\n397:                 'severity': 'blocking',\n398:                 'message': f'H2 header not ALL CAPS: \"{line}\"',\n399:                 'line': line,\n400:                 'auto_fixable': True,\n401:                 'fix': f'## {num}. {fixed_title}',\n402:                 'fix_hint': f'Change \"{section_text}\" to \"{section_text.upper()}\"'\n403:             })\n404: \n405:     return errors\n406: \n407: \n408: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n409: # 5. SECTION VALIDATION\n410: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n411: \n412: def validate_required_sections(content: str, doc_type_rules: Dict[str, Any]) -> List[Dict[str, Any]]:\n413:     \"\"\"Check that required sections are present.\"\"\"\n414:     errors = []\n415: \n416:     required = doc_type_rules.get('requiredSections', [])\n417:     section_aliases = doc_type_rules.get('sectionAliases', {})\n418: \n419:     # Compiled-contract commands are thin runtime dispatchers whose section content is\n420:     # rendered from a compiled source at invocation, not written in the .md file, so\n421:     # there is no prose section shape to require here.\n422:     contract_marker = doc_type_rules.get('compiledContractMarker')\n423:     if contract_marker and contract_marker in content:\n424:         return errors\n425: \n426:     # Build reverse alias map\n427:     reverse_aliases = {}\n428:     for alias, canonical in section_aliases.items():\n429:         reverse_aliases.setdefault(canonical, []).append(alias)\n430: \n431:     h2_pattern = re.compile(r'^## \\d+\\.\\s+[^\\n]+', re.MULTILINE)\n432:     headers = h2_pattern.findall(content)\n433: \n434:     # Keep both normalized and raw names for partial matching fallback\n435:     found_sections = set()\n436:     found_sections_raw = []\n437:     for header in headers:\n438:         match = re.search(r'^## \\d+\\.\\s+(?:[^\\w\\s]\\s+)?(.+)$', header)\n439:         if match:\n440:             raw_name = match.group(1).strip().lower()\n441:             section_name = normalize_section_name(raw_name)\n442:             found_sections.add(section_name)\n443:             found_sections_raw.append(raw_name)\n444: \n445:             if section_name in section_aliases:\n446:                 found_sections.add(section_aliases[section_name])\n447: \n448:     # A router command is a thin dispatcher (verify agent -> resolve mode/args -> hand\n449:     # off to owned presentation/workflow assets). It carries a router-specific section\n450:     # vocabulary instead of the general purpose/instructions sections, so detect that\n451:     # shape and require only the minimal router core, treating the rest as recommended.\n452:     # A section counts as present if its canonical name is a found header OR a known\n453:     # space-form alias of it normalizes (space->underscore) to a found header.\n454:     def section_present(canonical: str) -> bool:\n455:         if canonical in found_sections:\n456:             return True\n457:         for alias in reverse_aliases.get(canonical, []):\n458:             if alias.replace(' ', '_') in found_sections:\n459:                 return True\n460:         return False\n461: \n462:     detect_primary = doc_type_rules.get('routerDetectPrimary', [])\n463:     structural = doc_type_rules.get('routerStructuralSections', [])\n464:     is_router = (\n465:         any(section_present(sig) for sig in detect_primary)\n466:         or sum(1 for sig in structural if section_present(sig)) >= 2\n467:     )\n468:     if is_router:\n469:         required = doc_type_rules.get('routerRequiredSections', required)\n470: \n471:     for req_section in required:\n472:         found = req_section in found_sections\n473: \n474:         if not found:\n475:             aliases = reverse_aliases.get(req_section, [])\n476:             for alias in aliases:\n477:                 if alias.replace(' ', '_') in found_sections:\n478:                     found = True\n479:                     break\n480: \n481:         # Fuzzy match: accept if all required words appear in section name\n482:         if not found:\n483:             req_words = req_section.replace('_', ' ').split()\n484:             for raw_section in found_sections_raw:\n485:                 if all(word in raw_section for word in req_words):\n486:                     found = True\n487:                     break\n488: \n489:         if not found:\n490:             errors.append({\n491:                 'type': 'missing_required_section',\n492:                 'severity': 'blocking',\n493:                 'message': f'Missing required section: {req_section}',\n494:                 'fix_hint': f'Add section with name containing \"{req_section}\"'\n495:             })\n496: \n497:     # Router shape beyond the minimal core is recommended, not required: surface any\n498:     # missing canonical router section as a non-blocking warning so authors converge on\n499:     # the full vocabulary without failing incremental migrations.\n500:     if is_router:\n\n(Showing lines 1-500 of 928. Use offset=501 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# COMPONENT: README/DOCUMENTATION FORMAT VALIDATOR\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n\"\"\"\nREADME/Documentation Format Validator\n\nValidates markdown documentation against template rules to ensure\nconsistent formatting with proper TOC, H2 emojis, and section structure.\n\nUsage:\n    python validate_document.py <document.md> [--type readme|skill|reference|asset|agent|command|install_guide|spec|changelog]\n    python validate_document.py <document.md> --json\n    python validate_document.py <document.md> --fix [--dry-run]\n    python validate_document.py <document.md> --blocking-only\n\nExit Codes:\n    0 - Valid (no blocking errors)\n    1 - Invalid (blocking errors found)","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py","text":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# COMPONENT: README/DOCUMENTATION FORMAT VALIDATOR\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n\"\"\"\nREADME/Documentation Format Validator\n\nValidates markdown documentation against template rules to ensure\nconsistent formatting with proper TOC, H2 emojis, and section structure.\n\nUsage:\n    python validate_document.py <document.md> [--type readme|skill|reference|asset|agent|command|install_guide|spec|changelog]\n    python validate_document.py <document.md> --json\n    python validate_document.py <document.md> --fix [--dry-run]\n    python validate_document.py <document.md> --blocking-only\n\nExit Codes:\n    0 - Valid (no blocking errors)\n    1 - Invalid (blocking errors found)\n    2 - File not found or parse error\n\nExamples:\n    python validate_document.py README.md\n    python validate_document.py SKILL.md --type skill\n    python validate_document.py doc.md --json\n    python validate_document.py doc.md --fix --dry-run\n\"\"\"\n\nimport argparse\nimport json\nimport re\nimport sys\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import Any, Dict, List, Optional, Tuple\n\n\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 1. CONFIGURATION\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nEMOJI_PATTERN = re.compile(\n    \"[\"\n    \"\\U0001F300-\\U0001F9FF\"\n    \"\\U00002600-\\U000026FF\"\n    \"\\U00002700-\\U000027BF\"\n    \"\\U0001F600-\\U0001F64F\"\n    \"\\U0001F680-\\U0001F6FF\"\n    \"\\U0001F1E0-\\U0001F1FF\"\n    \"]\"\n)\n\n# Paths to exclude from validation (auto-generated, third-party, etc.)\nEXCLUDED_PATH_PATTERNS = [\n    '.pytest_cache',\n    'node_modules',\n    '__pycache__',\n    '.git',\n    'vendor',\n    'dist',\n    'build',\n    '.venv',\n    'venv',\n]\n\n# Third-party directories that use different README conventions\nTHIRD_PARTY_PATTERNS = [\n    # Add third-party patterns here if needed\n]\n\n# Template directories with intentionally minimal placeholder READMEs\nTEMPLATE_PATTERNS = [\n    'system-spec-kit/templates/',  # Spec folder templates are minimal by design\n]\n\n\ndef should_exclude_path(file_path: str) -> Tuple[bool, Optional[str]]:\n    \"\"\"Check if file path should be excluded from validation.\"\"\"\n    path_str = str(file_path)\n\n    # Check excluded patterns (auto-generated, dependencies)\n    for pattern in EXCLUDED_PATH_PATTERNS:\n        if f'/{pattern}/' in path_str or f'\\\\{pattern}\\\\' in path_str:\n            return True, f\"Excluded: matches pattern '{pattern}'\"\n\n    # Check third-party patterns\n    for pattern in THIRD_PARTY_PATTERNS:\n        if pattern in path_str:\n            return True, f\"Third-party: matches pattern '{pattern}'\"\n\n    # Check template patterns (intentionally minimal)\n    for pattern in TEMPLATE_PATTERNS:\n        if pattern in path_str:\n            return True, f\"Template: matches pattern '{pattern}' (intentionally minimal)\"\n\n    return False, None\n\n\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 2. UTILITIES\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef load_template_rules(script_dir: Path) -> Dict[str, Any]:\n    \"\"\"Load template_rules.json from assets folder.\"\"\"\n    rules_path = script_dir.parent / \"assets\" / \"template_rules.json\"\n    if not rules_path.exists():\n        print(f\"Error: template_rules.json not found at {rules_path}\", file=sys.stderr)\n        sys.exit(2)\n\n    with open(rules_path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:\n        return json.load(f)\n\n\ndef load_rules() -> Dict[str, Any]:\n    \"\"\"Load template rules for callers importing the validator module.\"\"\"\n    return load_template_rules(Path(__file__).parent)\n\n\ndef detect_document_type(file_path: str, content: str, rules: Dict[str, Any]) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Detect document type from file path or content.\"\"\"\n    path_lower = str(file_path).lower()\n\n    if '/manual_testing_playbook/' in path_lower or '\\\\manual_testing_playbook\\\\' in path_lower:\n        # A per-feature playbook leaf sits one level below the category root\n        # (manual_testing_playbook/<category>/<feature>.md). Classify by that structural\n        # position rather than an ordinal folder-name prefix, so category folders can be\n        # named by meaning alone. The root index file (whose parent IS the\n        # manual_testing_playbook dir) is intentionally excluded.\n        if Path(path_lower).parent.parent.name == 'manual_testing_playbook':\n            return 'playbook_feature'\n    # Per-feature catalog leaves sit one level below the catalog root\n    # (feature_catalog/<category>/<feature>.md). These carry the Validation And Tests\n    # table whose Type taxonomy and placeholder rows the generic readme path misses.\n    # Classify by structural position rather than an ordinal folder-name prefix; the\n    # root index file (whose parent IS the feature_catalog dir) stays excluded.\n    if '/feature_catalog/' in path_lower or '\\\\feature_catalog\\\\' in path_lower:\n        if Path(path_lower).parent.parent.name == 'feature_catalog':\n            return 'feature_catalog'\n    if '/command/' in path_lower or '\\\\command\\\\' in path_lower or '/commands/' in path_lower or '\\\\commands\\\\' in path_lower:\n        return 'command'\n    if '/install_guides/' in path_lower or '\\\\install_guides\\\\' in path_lower:\n        return 'install_guide'\n    if 'install_guide' in Path(path_lower).stem:\n        return 'install_guide'\n    # Changelog files: under .opencode/changelog/, .opencode/skills/*/changelog/,\n    # or spec-folder nested changelog/ subdirectories. Files match v{VERSION}.md or changelog-*.md\n    if '/changelog/' in path_lower or '\\\\changelog\\\\' in path_lower:\n        return 'changelog'\n    if path_lower.endswith('readme.md'):\n        return 'readme'\n    if path_lower.endswith('skill.md'):\n        return 'skill'\n    if '/specs/' in path_lower or '\\\\specs\\\\' in path_lower:\n        return 'spec'\n    if '/agents/' in path_lower or '\\\\agents\\\\' in path_lower or '/agent/' in path_lower or '\\\\agent\\\\' in path_lower:\n        return 'agent'\n    if '/references/' in path_lower or '\\\\references\\\\' in path_lower:\n        return 'reference'\n    if '/assets/' in path_lower or '\\\\assets\\\\' in path_lower:\n        return 'asset'\n\n    # Default to readme for general markdown\n    return 'readme'\n\n\ndef has_emoji(text: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Check if text contains an emoji.\"\"\"\n    return bool(EMOJI_PATTERN.search(text))\n\n\ndef extract_first_emoji(text: str) -> Optional[str]:\n    \"\"\"Extract the first emoji from text.\"\"\"\n    match = EMOJI_PATTERN.search(text)\n    return match.group(0) if match else None\n\n\ndef normalize_section_name(name: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Normalize section name for lookup in rules.\"\"\"\n    name = EMOJI_PATTERN.sub('', name)\n    name = name.strip().lower().replace(' ', '_')\n    name = re.sub(r'[^a-z0-9_]', '', name)\n    return name\n\n\ndef extract_section_name_text(text: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Extract the section name text after removing number prefix and emoji.\n\n    Examples:\n        \"1. 📖 Overview\" -> \"Overview\"\n        \"📖 OVERVIEW\" -> \"OVERVIEW\"\n        \"1. Overview\" -> \"Overview\"\n    \"\"\"\n    # Remove leading number and dot (e.g., \"1. \")\n    text = re.sub(r'^\\d+\\.\\s*', '', text)\n    # Remove emoji\n    text = EMOJI_PATTERN.sub('', text)\n    # Clean up whitespace\n    return text.strip()\n\n\ndef is_uppercase_section(text: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"\n    Check if section name is ALL CAPS.\n\n    Handles special characters like &, ', -, etc.\n    Only checks alphabetic characters for case.\n\n    Examples:\n        \"OVERVIEW\" -> True\n        \"Overview\" -> False\n        \"INSTALLATION & SETUP\" -> True\n        \"WHAT'S NEXT?\" -> True\n        \"MCP TOOLS\" -> True\n    \"\"\"\n    section_name = extract_section_name_text(text)\n    # Check if all alphabetic characters are uppercase\n    alpha_chars = [c for c in section_name if c.isalpha()]\n    if not alpha_chars:\n        return True  # No alphabetic chars, consider valid\n    return all(c.isupper() for c in alpha_chars)\n\n\ndef make_uppercase_section(text: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Convert section name to ALL CAPS while preserving structure.\n\n    Examples:\n        \"Overview\" -> \"OVERVIEW\"\n        \"Quick Start\" -> \"QUICK START\"\n        \"What's Next?\" -> \"WHAT'S NEXT?\"\n    \"\"\"\n    return text.upper()\n\n\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 3. TOC VALIDATION\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef validate_toc(content: str, doc_type_rules: Dict[str, Any], rules: Dict[str, Any]) -> List[Dict[str, Any]]:\n    \"\"\"Validate TABLE OF CONTENTS section.\"\"\"\n    errors = []\n\n    if not doc_type_rules.get('tocRequired', False):\n        return errors\n\n    # Accept variations with emoji (📑) or without\n    # Pattern: ## [optional emoji] TABLE OF CONTENTS\n    toc_match = re.search(\n        r'## (?:[^\\w\\s]\\s+)?TABLE OF CONTENTS\\s*\\n(.*?)(?=\\n---|\\n## |\\Z)',\n        content,\n        re.DOTALL | re.IGNORECASE\n    )\n\n    if not toc_match:\n        errors.append({\n            'type': 'missing_toc',\n            'severity': 'blocking',\n            'message': 'Missing TABLE OF CONTENTS section',\n            'fix_hint': 'Add \"## TABLE OF CONTENTS\" section with linked entries'\n        })\n        return errors\n\n    toc_content = toc_match.group(1)\n\n    for line_num, line in enumerate(toc_content.strip().split('\\n'), start=1):\n        line = line.strip()\n        if not line.startswith('- ['):\n            continue\n\n        # Double-dash anchors required for GitHub compatibility\n        anchor_match = re.search(r'\\(#(\\d+)-([a-z])', line)\n        if anchor_match:\n            errors.append({\n                'type': 'toc_single_dash_anchor',\n                'severity': 'blocking',\n                'message': f'TOC anchor uses single dash instead of double dash',\n                'line': line,\n                'fix_hint': f'Change \"#N-\" to \"#N--\" in anchor',\n                'auto_fixable': True,\n                'fix': line.replace(f'#{anchor_match.group(1)}-', f'#{anchor_match.group(1)}--')\n            })\n\n        entry_match = re.search(r'\\[(.+?)\\]', line)\n        if entry_match:\n            entry_text = entry_match.group(1)\n\n            # Check for ALL CAPS (only for readme type which requires it)\n            uppercase_required = doc_type_rules.get('tocUppercaseRequired', False)\n            if uppercase_required and not is_uppercase_section(entry_text):\n                section_text = extract_section_name_text(entry_text)\n                # Build fixed entry: preserve number and emoji, uppercase the name\n                # Pattern: \"N. EMOJI name\" -> \"N. EMOJI NAME\"\n                fixed_entry = re.sub(\n                    r'^(\\d+\\.\\s*)([^\\w\\s]\\s*)?(.+)$',\n                    lambda m: f\"{m.group(1)}{m.group(2) or ''}{m.group(3).upper()}\",\n                    entry_text\n                )\n                fixed_line = line.replace(f'[{entry_text}]', f'[{fixed_entry}]')\n\n                errors.append({\n                    'type': 'toc_not_uppercase',\n                    'severity': 'blocking',\n                    'message': f'TOC entry not ALL CAPS: \"{entry_text}\"',\n                    'line': line,\n                    'auto_fixable': True,\n                    'fix': fixed_line,\n                    'fix_hint': f'Change \"{section_text}\" to \"{section_text.upper()}\"'\n                })\n\n    return errors\n\n\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 4. HEADER VALIDATION\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef validate_h2_headers(content: str, doc_type_rules: Dict[str, Any], rules: Dict[str, Any]) -> List[Dict[str, Any]]:\n    \"\"\"Validate H2 header format and emojis.\"\"\"\n    errors = []\n\n    h2_pattern = re.compile(r'^## (\\d+)\\.\\s+(.+)$', re.MULTILINE)\n    matches = list(h2_pattern.finditer(content))\n\n    if not matches:\n        # No numbered H2 headers found - check if this is expected\n        # Some documents might use different header styles\n        return errors\n\n    expected_num = 1\n    emoji_required = doc_type_rules.get('h2EmojiRequired', True)\n    section_emojis = doc_type_rules.get('sectionEmojis', {})\n    section_aliases = doc_type_rules.get('sectionAliases', {})\n\n    for match in matches:\n        num = int(match.group(1))\n        title = match.group(2).strip()\n        line = match.group(0)\n\n        if num != expected_num:\n            errors.append({\n                'type': 'non_sequential_numbering',\n                'severity': 'warning',\n                'message': f'Non-sequential section number: expected {expected_num}, found {num}',\n                'line': line\n            })\n        expected_num = num + 1\n\n        if emoji_required:\n            title_has_emoji = has_emoji(title)\n\n            if not title_has_emoji:\n                section_name = normalize_section_name(title)\n\n                if section_name in section_aliases:\n                    section_name = section_aliases[section_name]\n\n                expected_emoji = section_emojis.get(section_name)\n\n                # Fallback: match ignoring underscores for flexibility\n                if not expected_emoji:\n                    section_name_no_underscore = section_name.replace('_', '')\n                    for key, emoji in section_emojis.items():\n                        if key.replace('_', '') == section_name_no_underscore:\n                            expected_emoji = emoji\n                            break\n\n                errors.append({\n                    'type': 'missing_h2_emoji',\n                    'severity': 'blocking',\n                    'message': f'H2 header missing emoji: \"{line}\"',\n                    'line': line,\n                    'section_name': section_name,\n                    'expected_emoji': expected_emoji,\n                    'auto_fixable': expected_emoji is not None,\n                    'fix': f'## {num}. {expected_emoji} {title}' if expected_emoji else None,\n                    'fix_hint': f'Add {expected_emoji} after \"{num}.\"' if expected_emoji else 'Add appropriate emoji after section number'\n                })\n\n        # Check for ALL CAPS (only for document types that require it)\n        uppercase_required = doc_type_rules.get('h2UppercaseRequired', False)\n        if uppercase_required and not is_uppercase_section(title):\n            section_text = extract_section_name_text(title)\n            # Extract emoji if present\n            emoji = extract_first_emoji(title)\n\n            if emoji:\n                # Has emoji: \"EMOJI name\" -> \"EMOJI NAME\"\n                title_after_emoji = EMOJI_PATTERN.sub('', title).strip()\n                fixed_title = f'{emoji} {title_after_emoji.upper()}'\n            else:\n                # No emoji: just uppercase\n                fixed_title = title.upper()\n\n            errors.append({\n                'type': 'h2_not_uppercase',\n                'severity': 'blocking',\n                'message': f'H2 header not ALL CAPS: \"{line}\"',\n                'line': line,\n                'auto_fixable': True,\n                'fix': f'## {num}. {fixed_title}',\n                'fix_hint': f'Change \"{section_text}\" to \"{section_text.upper()}\"'\n            })\n\n    return errors\n\n\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 5. SECTION VALIDATION\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef validate_required_sections(content: str, doc_type_rules: Dict[str, Any]) -> List[Dict[str, Any]]:\n    \"\"\"Check that required sections are present.\"\"\"\n    errors = []\n\n    required = doc_type_rules.get('requiredSections', [])\n    section_aliases = doc_type_rules.get('sectionAliases', {})\n\n    # Compiled-contract commands are thin runtime dispatchers whose section content is\n    # rendered from a compiled source at invocation, not written in the .md file, so\n    # there is no prose section shape to require here.\n    contract_marker = doc_type_rules.get('compiledContractMarker')\n    if contract_marker and contract_marker in content:\n        return errors\n\n    # Build reverse alias map\n    reverse_aliases = {}\n    for alias, canonical in section_aliases.items():\n        reverse_aliases.setdefault(canonical, []).append(alias)\n\n    h2_pattern = re.compile(r'^## \\d+\\.\\s+[^\\n]+', re.MULTILINE)\n    headers = h2_pattern.findall(content)\n\n    # Keep both normalized and raw names for partial matching fallback\n    found_sections = set()\n    found_sections_raw = []\n    for header in headers:\n        match = re.search(r'^## \\d+\\.\\s+(?:[^\\w\\s]\\s+)?(.+)$', header)\n        if match:\n            raw_name = match.group(1).strip().lower()\n            section_name = normalize_section_name(raw_name)\n            found_sections.add(section_name)\n            found_sections_raw.append(raw_name)\n\n            if section_name in section_aliases:\n                found_sections.add(section_aliases[section_name])\n\n    # A router command is a thin dispatcher (verify agent -> resolve mode/args -> hand\n    # off to owned presentation/workflow assets). It carries a router-specific section\n    # vocabulary instead of the general purpose/instructions sections, so detect that\n    # shape and require only the minimal router core, treating the rest as recommended.\n    # A section counts as present if its canonical name is a found header OR a known\n    # space-form alias of it normalizes (space->underscore) to a found header.\n    def section_present(canonical: str) -> bool:\n        if canonical in found_sections:\n            return True\n        for alias in reverse_aliases.get(canonical, []):\n            if alias.replace(' ', '_') in found_sections:\n                return True\n        return False\n\n    detect_primary = doc_type_rules.get('routerDetectPrimary', [])\n    structural = doc_type_rules.get('routerStructuralSections', [])\n    is_router = (\n        any(section_present(sig) for sig in detect_primary)\n        or sum(1 for sig in structural if section_present(sig)) >= 2\n    )\n    if is_router:\n        required = doc_type_rules.get('routerRequiredSections', required)\n\n    for req_section in required:\n        found = req_section in found_sections\n\n        if not found:\n            aliases = reverse_aliases.get(req_section, [])\n            for alias in aliases:\n                if alias.replace(' ', '_') in found_sections:\n                    found = True\n                    break\n\n        # Fuzzy match: accept if all required words appear in section name\n        if not found:\n            req_words = req_section.replace('_', ' ').split()\n            for raw_section in found_sections_raw:\n                if all(word in raw_section for word in req_words):\n                    found = True\n                    break\n\n        if not found:\n            errors.append({\n                'type': 'missing_required_section',\n                'severity': 'blocking',\n                'message': f'Missing required section: {req_section}',\n                'fix_hint': f'Add section with name containing \"{req_section}\"'\n            })\n\n    # Router shape beyond the minimal core is recommended, not required: surface any\n    # missing canonical router section as a non-blocking warning so authors converge on\n    # the full vocabulary without failing incremental migrations.\n    if is_router:","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":500,"totalLines":928,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py","time":{"start":1783915666921,"end":1783915666924}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d074688ef23ef0016a546492c7ac8191b85142a0cf0a2dbe"}},"id":"prt_f59a8ddbb001h2X6OrSiHZjr7v","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a8967f0016hU7NQSPitq0xc"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915667073,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_JvwblVwTrqQb3FqhCqYO2FT8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/implementation_workflows/validation_minification_and_cdn.md","offset":1,"limit":100},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/implementation_workflows/validation_minification_and_cdn.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment\n3: description: Three specialized workflows for writing robust frontend code with proper timing, validation, and cache management. — Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"defense in depth\"\n6:   - \"minification cdn deployment\"\n7:   - \"defense in patterns\"\n8:   - \"webflow defense in\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.10\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment\n15: \n16: Three specialized workflows for writing robust frontend code with proper timing, validation, and cache management. — Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Three deployment-hardening workflows: defense-in-depth input validation, build-time minification, and CDN cache management, with a quick-reference summary.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: Use this reference when implementing or troubleshooting defense-in-depth validation, minification & cdn deployment.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH VALIDATION\n33: \n34: **When to use**: Form handling, API calls, DOM manipulation, user input, third-party data integration\n35: \n36: ### Core Principle\n37: \n38: Validate at EVERY layer data passes through. Make bugs structurally impossible.\n39: \n40: ### The Four Layers\n41: \n42: #### Layer 1: Entry Point Validation\n43: \n44: Reject obviously invalid input at function boundary.\n45: \n46: ```javascript\n47: function init_video(video_element, config) {\n48:   // Layer 1: Entry validation\n49:   if (!video_element) {\n50:     console.error('[Video] Element is required');\n51:     return null;\n52:   }\n53: \n54:   if (!(video_element instanceof HTMLVideoElement)) {\n55:     console.error('[Video] Must be HTMLVideoElement, got:', video_element);\n56:     return null;\n57:   }\n58: \n59:   if (!config || typeof config !== 'object') {\n60:     console.error('[Video] Config must be object, got:', config);\n61:     return null;\n62:   }\n63: \n64:   // Proceed with initialization...\n65: }\n66: ```\n67: \n68: #### Layer 2: Processing Validation\n69: \n70: Ensure data makes sense for this operation.\n71: \n72: ```javascript\n73: function update_video_source(video_element, new_source) {\n74:   // Layer 1: Entry validation\n75:   if (!video_element || !new_source) {\n76:     console.error('[Video] Missing required parameters');\n77:     return false;\n78:   }\n79: \n80:   // Layer 2: Processing validation\n81:   if (typeof new_source !== 'string' || new_source.trim() === '') {\n82:     console.error('[Video] Source must be non-empty string');\n83:     return false;\n84:   }\n85: \n86:   if (!new_source.match(/\\.(mp4|webm|m3u8)$/i)) {\n87:     console.error('[Video] Invalid video format:', new_source);\n88:     return false;\n89:   }\n90: \n91:   // Safe to proceed\n92:   video_element.src = new_source;\n93:   return true;\n94: }\n95: ```\n96: \n97: #### Layer 3: Output Validation\n98: \n99: Verify results before using them.\n100: \n\n(Showing lines 1-100 of 329. Use offset=101 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment\ndescription: Three specialized workflows for writing robust frontend code with proper timing, validation, and cache management. — Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"defense in depth\"\n  - \"minification cdn deployment\"\n  - \"defense in patterns\"\n  - \"webflow defense in\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.10\n---\n\n# Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment\n\nThree specialized workflows for writing robust frontend code with proper timing, validation, and cache management. — Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/implementation_workflows/validation_minification_and_cdn.md","text":"---\ntitle: Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment\ndescription: Three specialized workflows for writing robust frontend code with proper timing, validation, and cache management. — Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"defense in depth\"\n  - \"minification cdn deployment\"\n  - \"defense in patterns\"\n  - \"webflow defense in\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.10\n---\n\n# Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment\n\nThree specialized workflows for writing robust frontend code with proper timing, validation, and cache management. — Defense-in-Depth Validation, Minification & CDN Deployment.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThree deployment-hardening workflows: defense-in-depth input validation, build-time minification, and CDN cache management, with a quick-reference summary.\n\n### When to Use\n\nUse this reference when implementing or troubleshooting defense-in-depth validation, minification & cdn deployment.\n\n---\n\n## 2. DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH VALIDATION\n\n**When to use**: Form handling, API calls, DOM manipulation, user input, third-party data integration\n\n### Core Principle\n\nValidate at EVERY layer data passes through. Make bugs structurally impossible.\n\n### The Four Layers\n\n#### Layer 1: Entry Point Validation\n\nReject obviously invalid input at function boundary.\n\n```javascript\nfunction init_video(video_element, config) {\n  // Layer 1: Entry validation\n  if (!video_element) {\n    console.error('[Video] Element is required');\n    return null;\n  }\n\n  if (!(video_element instanceof HTMLVideoElement)) {\n    console.error('[Video] Must be HTMLVideoElement, got:', video_element);\n    return null;\n  }\n\n  if (!config || typeof config !== 'object') {\n    console.error('[Video] Config must be object, got:', config);\n    return null;\n  }\n\n  // Proceed with initialization...\n}\n```\n\n#### Layer 2: Processing Validation\n\nEnsure data makes sense for this operation.\n\n```javascript\nfunction update_video_source(video_element, new_source) {\n  // Layer 1: Entry validation\n  if (!video_element || !new_source) {\n    console.error('[Video] Missing required parameters');\n    return false;\n  }\n\n  // Layer 2: Processing validation\n  if (typeof new_source !== 'string' || new_source.trim() === '') {\n    console.error('[Video] Source must be non-empty string');\n    return false;\n  }\n\n  if (!new_source.match(/\\.(mp4|webm|m3u8)$/i)) {\n    console.error('[Video] Invalid video format:', new_source);\n    return false;\n  }\n\n  // Safe to proceed\n  video_element.src = new_source;\n  return true;\n}\n```\n\n#### Layer 3: Output Validation\n\nVerify results before using them.\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":100,"totalLines":329,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/implementation_workflows/validation_minification_and_cdn.md","time":{"start":1783915667060,"end":1783915667063}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d074688ef23ef0016a546492c7b48191805bdb810f90b750"}},"id":"prt_f59a8de130019Y9EN1g2OmetKh","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a8967f0016hU7NQSPitq0xc"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915667125,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_MXwbvJKXOA8hFyNtZmJKRMJ4","state":{"status":"error","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/config/quality_standards/validation_and_modularization.md","offset":1,"limit":100},"error":"File not found: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/config/quality_standards/validation_and_modularization.md","time":{"start":1783915667121,"end":1783915667124}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d074688ef23ef0016a546492c7b881919c627eae59d07e85"}},"id":"prt_f59a8dea0001vuiLTGleSZt217","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a8967f0016hU7NQSPitq0xc"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915667128,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ETqEf3s6EtkRlIpRYG7jOYJL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview_header_and_comments.md","offset":1,"limit":100},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview_header_and_comments.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Code Quality Checklist\n3: description: Validation checklist for JavaScript and CSS code quality and style compliance.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow code quality checklist\"\n6:   - \"javascript css style compliance\"\n7:   - \"file header checks webflow\"\n8:   - \"review baseline handoff\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.17\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Code Quality Checklist\n15: \n16: Validation checklist for JavaScript and CSS code quality and style compliance.\n17: \n18: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n19: \n20: ### Purpose\n21: \n22: Validate code against style standards before claiming implementation is complete. This checklist ensures consistent, maintainable code across the codebase.\n23: \n24: ### Usage\n25: \n26: 1. **Load** this checklist when completing code implementation\n27: 2. **Identify** file type (JavaScript → Sections 2-7, CSS → Section 8)\n28: 3. **Validate** each applicable item against the code\n29: 4. **Mark** items `[x]` when verified\n30: 5. **Block** completion if any P0 item fails\n31: 6. **Document** P2 deferrals with reasons\n32: \n33: ### Language Coverage\n34: \n35: | Language | File Extension | Checklist Sections |\n36: |----------|----------------|-------------------|\n37: | JavaScript | `.js` | Sections 2-7 |\n38: | CSS | `.css` | Section 8 |\n39: \n40: ### Review Baseline Handoff\n41: \n42: For formal findings-first review output, run `sk-code`'s code-review mode as the baseline and use this checklist as the web overlay.\n43: \n44: - Severity model and review output contract: `sk-code/code-review/references/quick_reference.md`\n45: - Baseline security/quality/test review checks: `sk-code`'s code-review mode references\n46: - This checklist: web-specific JavaScript/CSS standards evidence\n47: \n48: ### Source Standards (per-language tree)\n49: \n50: - [shared/cross_language_rules.md](../../../code-webflow/references/shared/cross_language_rules.md) - Cross-language rules (file naming, comment WHY-not-WHAT, banner format, platform prefixes)\n51: - [javascript/style_guide.md](../../../code-webflow/references/javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md) - JS naming (`snake_case`), file structure, formatting, JSDoc, debug logging\n52: - [javascript/quality_standards.md](../../../code-webflow/references/javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md) - JS defensive patterns + JS naming/init enforcement\n53: - [css/style_guide.md](../../../code-webflow/references/css/style_guide.md) - CSS naming (BEM), custom properties, attribute selectors, animation CSS, file org\n54: - [css/quality_standards.md](../../../code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) - CSS quality patterns + CSS enforcement subsections\n55: \n56: ---\n57: \n58: ## 2. FILE HEADER CHECKS\n59: \n60: **Applies to:** JavaScript (`.js`)\n61: \n62: **Reference:** [code_style_guide.md Section 3](../../../code-webflow/references/javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md)\n63: \n64: ### File Header Format\n65: \n66: - [ ] **[P0] CHK-HDR-01**: File starts with three-line header\n67: - [ ] **[P0] CHK-HDR-02**: Header uses box-drawing character `─` (U+2500), not hyphen `-`\n68: - [ ] **[P0] CHK-HDR-03**: Header line width is 67 characters\n69: - [ ] **[P1] CHK-HDR-04**: Category label is ALL CAPS\n70: - [ ] **[P1] CHK-HDR-05**: Component name is descriptive (2-4 words)\n71: - [ ] **[P2] CHK-HDR-06**: No metadata (dates, authors, version numbers) in header\n72: - [ ] **[P1] CHK-CMT-01**: No ephemeral artifact ids in any comment (ticket/ClickUp ids, spec/phase/packet numbers, ADR ids) — keep the WHY; see [references/universal/code_style_guide.md](../../../shared/references/universal/code_style_guide.md) §4\n73: \n74: **Compliant Example:**\n75: ```javascript\n76: // ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n77: // VIDEO: BACKGROUND HLS HOVER\n78: // ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n79: ```\n80: \n81: **Non-Compliant Examples:**\n82: ```javascript\n83: // WRONG: Using hyphens instead of box-drawing characters\n84: // -------------------------------------------------------------------\n85: // VIDEO: BACKGROUND HLS HOVER\n86: // -------------------------------------------------------------------\n87: \n88: // WRONG: Missing header entirely\n89: (() => {\n90:   // code starts without header\n91: })();\n92: \n93: // WRONG: Metadata in header\n94: // ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n95: // VIDEO: BACKGROUND HLS HOVER - Created 2024-01-15 by Developer\n96: // ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n97: ```\n98: \n99: ---\n100: \n\n(Showing lines 1-100 of 213. Use offset=101 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Code Quality Checklist\ndescription: Validation checklist for JavaScript and CSS code quality and style compliance.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow code quality checklist\"\n  - \"javascript css style compliance\"\n  - \"file header checks webflow\"\n  - \"review baseline handoff\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.17\n---\n\n# Code Quality Checklist\n\nValidation checklist for JavaScript and CSS code quality and style compliance.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview_header_and_comments.md","text":"---\ntitle: Code Quality Checklist\ndescription: Validation checklist for JavaScript and CSS code quality and style compliance.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow code quality checklist\"\n  - \"javascript css style compliance\"\n  - \"file header checks webflow\"\n  - \"review baseline handoff\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.17\n---\n\n# Code Quality Checklist\n\nValidation checklist for JavaScript and CSS code quality and style compliance.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nValidate code against style standards before claiming implementation is complete. This checklist ensures consistent, maintainable code across the codebase.\n\n### Usage\n\n1. **Load** this checklist when completing code implementation\n2. **Identify** file type (JavaScript → Sections 2-7, CSS → Section 8)\n3. **Validate** each applicable item against the code\n4. **Mark** items `[x]` when verified\n5. **Block** completion if any P0 item fails\n6. **Document** P2 deferrals with reasons\n\n### Language Coverage\n\n| Language | File Extension | Checklist Sections |\n|----------|----------------|-------------------|\n| JavaScript | `.js` | Sections 2-7 |\n| CSS | `.css` | Section 8 |\n\n### Review Baseline Handoff\n\nFor formal findings-first review output, run `sk-code`'s code-review mode as the baseline and use this checklist as the web overlay.\n\n- Severity model and review output contract: `sk-code/code-review/references/quick_reference.md`\n- Baseline security/quality/test review checks: `sk-code`'s code-review mode references\n- This checklist: web-specific JavaScript/CSS standards evidence\n\n### Source Standards (per-language tree)\n\n- [shared/cross_language_rules.md](../../../code-webflow/references/shared/cross_language_rules.md) - Cross-language rules (file naming, comment WHY-not-WHAT, banner format, platform prefixes)\n- [javascript/style_guide.md](../../../code-webflow/references/javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md) - JS naming (`snake_case`), file structure, formatting, JSDoc, debug logging\n- [javascript/quality_standards.md](../../../code-webflow/references/javascript/quality_standards/init_dom_error_and_async.md) - JS defensive patterns + JS naming/init enforcement\n- [css/style_guide.md](../../../code-webflow/references/css/style_guide.md) - CSS naming (BEM), custom properties, attribute selectors, animation CSS, file org\n- [css/quality_standards.md](../../../code-webflow/references/css/quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) - CSS quality patterns + CSS enforcement subsections\n\n---\n\n## 2. FILE HEADER CHECKS\n\n**Applies to:** JavaScript (`.js`)\n\n**Reference:** [code_style_guide.md Section 3](../../../code-webflow/references/javascript/style_guide/overview_naming_and_structure.md)\n\n### File Header Format\n\n- [ ] **[P0] CHK-HDR-01**: File starts with three-line header\n- [ ] **[P0] CHK-HDR-02**: Header uses box-drawing character `─` (U+2500), not hyphen `-`\n- [ ] **[P0] CHK-HDR-03**: Header line width is 67 characters\n- [ ] **[P1] CHK-HDR-04**: Category label is ALL CAPS\n- [ ] **[P1] CHK-HDR-05**: Component name is descriptive (2-4 words)\n- [ ] **[P2] CHK-HDR-06**: No metadata (dates, authors, version numbers) in header\n- [ ] **[P1] CHK-CMT-01**: No ephemeral artifact ids in any comment (ticket/ClickUp ids, spec/phase/packet numbers, ADR ids) — keep the WHY; see [references/universal/code_style_guide.md](../../../shared/references/universal/code_style_guide.md) §4\n\n**Compliant Example:**\n```javascript\n// ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// VIDEO: BACKGROUND HLS HOVER\n// ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n```\n\n**Non-Compliant Examples:**\n```javascript\n// WRONG: Using hyphens instead of box-drawing characters\n// -------------------------------------------------------------------\n// VIDEO: BACKGROUND HLS HOVER\n// -------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n// WRONG: Missing header entirely\n(() => {\n  // code starts without header\n})();\n\n// WRONG: Metadata in header\n// ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// VIDEO: BACKGROUND HLS HOVER - Created 2024-01-15 by Developer\n// ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n```\n\n---\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":100,"totalLines":213,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview_header_and_comments.md","time":{"start":1783915667123,"end":1783915667128}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d074688ef23ef0016a546492c7bc81919474bac043de6d8c"}},"id":"prt_f59a8deb2001gED39sRZjWmGJ4","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a8967f0016hU7NQSPitq0xc"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915667140,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_6tGOlmCyxTyq3CiF4YFfOqiR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/webflow_constraints.md","offset":140,"limit":50},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/webflow_constraints.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n140: | Third-party | Yes | Yes | Full control |\n141: \n142: ---\n143: \n144: ## 7. WHAT IS CONTROLLABLE\n145: \n146: Despite platform constraints, you CAN optimize:\n147: \n148: - **Third-party scripts** (GTM, analytics) - Delay with requestIdleCallback\n149: - **Custom JavaScript loading** - Full async/defer control\n150: - **Custom CSS** (async pattern) - Preload with onload swap\n151: - **Resource hints** (preconnect, preload) - Add via Project Settings\n152: - **Image optimization** - WebP, lazy loading, srcset\n153: - **Video loading strategy** - Poster images, lazy load, HLS\n154: \n155: ---\n156: \n157: ## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n158: \n159: ### Internal References\n160: \n161: - [`../implementation/performance_patterns/overview_and_checklist.md`](../implementation/performance_patterns/overview_and_checklist.md) - Umbrella performance checklist + budgets + anti-patterns (high-level entry point)\n162: - [cwv_remediation.md](./cwv_remediation.md) - Core Web Vitals optimization patterns\n163: - [third_party.md](./third_party.md) - Third-party script optimization\n164: - [resource_loading.md](./resource_loading.md) - Resource hints and loading strategies\n165: \n166: ### Decision Records\n167: \n168: See [decision-record.md](/specs/005-example.com/024-performance-optimization/decision-record.md) for implementation decisions:\n169: \n170: - **DR-002**: TypeKit preconnect implementation\n171: - **DR-004**: GTM delay strategy (requestIdleCallback)\n172: - **DR-005**: Swiper CSS async loading pattern\n\n(End of file - total 172 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"| Third-party | Yes | Yes | Full control |\n\n---\n\n## 7. WHAT IS CONTROLLABLE\n\nDespite platform constraints, you CAN optimize:\n\n- **Third-party scripts** (GTM, analytics) - Delay with requestIdleCallback\n- **Custom JavaScript loading** - Full async/defer control\n- **Custom CSS** (async pattern) - Preload with onload swap\n- **Resource hints** (preconnect, preload) - Add via Project Settings\n- **Image optimization** - WebP, lazy loading, srcset\n- **Video loading strategy** - Poster images, lazy load, HLS\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n### Internal References","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/webflow_constraints.md","text":"| Third-party | Yes | Yes | Full control |\n\n---\n\n## 7. WHAT IS CONTROLLABLE\n\nDespite platform constraints, you CAN optimize:\n\n- **Third-party scripts** (GTM, analytics) - Delay with requestIdleCallback\n- **Custom JavaScript loading** - Full async/defer control\n- **Custom CSS** (async pattern) - Preload with onload swap\n- **Resource hints** (preconnect, preload) - Add via Project Settings\n- **Image optimization** - WebP, lazy loading, srcset\n- **Video loading strategy** - Poster images, lazy load, HLS\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n### Internal References\n\n- [`../implementation/performance_patterns/overview_and_checklist.md`](../implementation/performance_patterns/overview_and_checklist.md) - Umbrella performance checklist + budgets + anti-patterns (high-level entry point)\n- [cwv_remediation.md](./cwv_remediation.md) - Core Web Vitals optimization patterns\n- [third_party.md](./third_party.md) - Third-party script optimization\n- [resource_loading.md](./resource_loading.md) - Resource hints and loading strategies\n\n### Decision Records\n\nSee [decision-record.md](/specs/005-example.com/024-performance-optimization/decision-record.md) for implementation decisions:\n\n- **DR-002**: TypeKit preconnect implementation\n- **DR-004**: GTM delay strategy (requestIdleCallback)\n- **DR-005**: Swiper CSS async loading pattern","lineStart":140,"lineEnd":172,"totalLines":172,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/performance/webflow_constraints.md","time":{"start":1783915667137,"end":1783915667140}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d074688ef23ef0016a546492c7c481918151622cd9247703"}},"id":"prt_f59a8deb5001E5czNK4J09mvIe","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a8967f0016hU7NQSPitq0xc"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915667154,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_tCfqPJ3pZSs9QPVtei1TnBA5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md","offset":55,"limit":35},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n55: \n56: A new file at `references/webflow/html/quality_standards.md` (354 lines) gives HTML the same quality-standards companion that JavaScript and CSS already had. The previous gap meant data-attribute hygiene rules, ARIA state-sync enforcement, custom embed validation, and head/footer panel structure validation lived nowhere or were scattered across other docs. The new file consolidates all of these into one enforcement reference.\n57: \n58: ---\n59: \n60: ## Bug Fixes\n61: \n62: A multi-AI council audit (three lenses: maintainability, discoverability, symmetry) over the post-refactor tree surfaced 14 alignment findings. All 14 are resolved in this release.\n63: \n64: #### Restored a quick-reference file lost during refactor\n65: \n66: A python regex pass during the refactor accidentally deleted `webflow/javascript/quick_reference.md` from disk. The file was untracked at the time of the recovery so `git checkout HEAD --` did not restore it. Four other files were already cross-referencing the missing file. This release restores `webflow/javascript/quick_reference.md` (294 lines covering pre-commit checklist, code snippets like `waitForElement` and `waitForLibrary`, eleven one-liners for MutationObserver, IntersectionObserver, Lenis scrollTo, Motion.dev animate and inView, custom event dispatch, optional chaining, and form validation classes).\n67: \n68: &nbsp;\n69: \n70: #### Fixed stale references the bulk sweep missed\n71: \n72: The Phase 3 bulk sed pass missed six references in `webflow/shared/enforcement.md` because the sweep regex did not match the bare-filename references like `[code_quality_standards.md](code_quality_standards.md)` (no path prefix). This release replaces all six with the correct per-language tree paths and rewrites the surrounding \"Related Documents\" block as a five-link tree map.\n73: \n74: &nbsp;\n75: \n76: #### Fixed broken relative paths in moved files\n77: \n78: When `implementation/css_patterns.md` moved to `css/patterns.md`, three internal links continued pointing at the old `./` (same directory) path that no longer resolved (`./animation_workflows.md`, `./webflow_patterns.md` are in `../implementation/`, not the new `css/` location). Three more broken paths in `shared/dev_workflow.md` section 9 pointed at sibling files that actually live in `../implementation/` and `../debugging/`. This release fixes all six paths with the correct relative prefixes.\n79: \n80: &nbsp;\n81: \n82: #### Added inbound references to orphan deep-dive\n83: \n84: The 1,263-line `css/patterns.md` had zero inbound references after the move (orphan: a new contributor would never discover it through the reference tree). This release adds inbound links from `css/style_guide.md`, `css/quality_standards.md`, `implementation/webflow_patterns.md`, and `implementation/animation_workflows.md`.\n85: \n86: &nbsp;\n87: \n88: #### Added bidirectional cross-references between performance docs\n89: \n\n(Showing lines 55-89 of 212. Use offset=90 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\nA new file at `references/webflow/html/quality_standards.md` (354 lines) gives HTML the same quality-standards companion that JavaScript and CSS already had. The previous gap meant data-attribute hygiene rules, ARIA state-sync enforcement, custom embed validation, and head/footer panel structure validation lived nowhere or were scattered across other docs. The new file consolidates all of these into one enforcement reference.\n\n---\n\n## Bug Fixes\n\nA multi-AI council audit (three lenses: maintainability, discoverability, symmetry) over the post-refactor tree surfaced 14 alignment findings. All 14 are resolved in this release.\n\n#### Restored a quick-reference file lost during refactor\n\nA python regex pass during the refactor accidentally deleted `webflow/javascript/quick_reference.md` from disk. The file was untracked at the time of the recovery so `git checkout HEAD --` did not restore it. Four other files were already cross-referencing the missing file. This release restores `webflow/javascript/quick_reference.md` (294 lines covering pre-commit checklist, code snippets like `waitForElement` and `waitForLibrary`, eleven one-liners for MutationObserver, IntersectionObserver, Lenis scrollTo, Motion.dev animate and inView, custom event dispatch, optional chaining, and form validation classes).\n\n&nbsp;\n\n#### Fixed stale references the bulk sweep missed\n\nThe Phase 3 bulk sed pass missed six references in `webflow/shared/enforcement.md` because the sweep regex did not match the bare-filename references like `[code_quality_standards.md](code_quality_standards.md)` (no path prefix). This release replaces all six with the correct per-language tree paths and rewrites the surrounding \"Related Documents\" block as a five-link tree map.\n\n&nbsp;","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md","text":"\nA new file at `references/webflow/html/quality_standards.md` (354 lines) gives HTML the same quality-standards companion that JavaScript and CSS already had. The previous gap meant data-attribute hygiene rules, ARIA state-sync enforcement, custom embed validation, and head/footer panel structure validation lived nowhere or were scattered across other docs. The new file consolidates all of these into one enforcement reference.\n\n---\n\n## Bug Fixes\n\nA multi-AI council audit (three lenses: maintainability, discoverability, symmetry) over the post-refactor tree surfaced 14 alignment findings. All 14 are resolved in this release.\n\n#### Restored a quick-reference file lost during refactor\n\nA python regex pass during the refactor accidentally deleted `webflow/javascript/quick_reference.md` from disk. The file was untracked at the time of the recovery so `git checkout HEAD --` did not restore it. Four other files were already cross-referencing the missing file. This release restores `webflow/javascript/quick_reference.md` (294 lines covering pre-commit checklist, code snippets like `waitForElement` and `waitForLibrary`, eleven one-liners for MutationObserver, IntersectionObserver, Lenis scrollTo, Motion.dev animate and inView, custom event dispatch, optional chaining, and form validation classes).\n\n&nbsp;\n\n#### Fixed stale references the bulk sweep missed\n\nThe Phase 3 bulk sed pass missed six references in `webflow/shared/enforcement.md` because the sweep regex did not match the bare-filename references like `[code_quality_standards.md](code_quality_standards.md)` (no path prefix). This release replaces all six with the correct per-language tree paths and rewrites the surrounding \"Related Documents\" block as a five-link tree map.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n#### Fixed broken relative paths in moved files\n\nWhen `implementation/css_patterns.md` moved to `css/patterns.md`, three internal links continued pointing at the old `./` (same directory) path that no longer resolved (`./animation_workflows.md`, `./webflow_patterns.md` are in `../implementation/`, not the new `css/` location). Three more broken paths in `shared/dev_workflow.md` section 9 pointed at sibling files that actually live in `../implementation/` and `../debugging/`. This release fixes all six paths with the correct relative prefixes.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n#### Added inbound references to orphan deep-dive\n\nThe 1,263-line `css/patterns.md` had zero inbound references after the move (orphan: a new contributor would never discover it through the reference tree). This release adds inbound links from `css/style_guide.md`, `css/quality_standards.md`, `implementation/webflow_patterns.md`, and `implementation/animation_workflows.md`.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n#### Added bidirectional cross-references between performance docs\n","lineStart":55,"lineEnd":89,"totalLines":212,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md","time":{"start":1783915667151,"end":1783915667153}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09d074688ef23ef0016a546492c7cc81919c7079619bd5f48e"}},"id":"prt_f59a8dec6001Z06URlqE9D8L2T","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a8967f0016hU7NQSPitq0xc"}}
