{"type":"text","timestamp":1783915761217,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"id":"prt_f59aa05a1001EP445IpM2GFPO2","messageID":"msg_f59a9e074001szttQ6FV3B4V4D","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","type":"text","text":"The first full-corpus pass found four candidate regressions after remediation: one intro/Purpose containment duplicate remains, two reference files lack the required `### When to Use`, and one Rust reference has an H3 inside the H1-to-OVERVIEW intro region. The generic validator still reports zero because it does not enforce these semantic/template details; I am re-reading each candidate and reconciling the apparent `155` current-file count against the packet’s `163` claim before assigning severity.","time":{"start":1783915742625,"end":1783915761210},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0022882c602ad73d016a5464de9e78819181df50a545b49bd8","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915761294,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_PbW0BqtHrgPNvNo87Zuxu1b5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","offset":1,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n3: description: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n6:   - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n7:   - \"rust style guidance\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: implementation\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: ---\n12: \n13: # Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n14: \n15: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ### Error Style\n20: \n21: Core public operations return domain-specific `Result` values backed by `thiserror`.\n22: \n23: ```rust\n24: use thiserror::Error;\n25: \n26: #[derive(Debug, Error)]\n27: pub enum RankingError {\n28:     #[error(\"candidate identifier must not be empty\")]\n29:     EmptyIdentifier,\n30: \n31:     #[error(\"candidate score must be finite\")]\n32:     NonFiniteScore,\n33: \n34:     #[error(\"candidate limit {limit} exceeds maximum {maximum}\")]\n35:     LimitExceeded {\n36:         limit: u32,\n37:         maximum: u32,\n38:     },\n39: }\n40: ```\n41: \n42: Rules:\n43: \n44: - Core errors contain adapter-relevant structured context.\n45: - Core errors contain no napi-rs, WASM, or Node runtime types.\n46: - `anyhow` is prohibited in pure-core public APIs and exported functions.\n47: - `anyhow` MAY be used in sidecar `main`, build tooling, and the outermost non-ABI shell.\n48: - Every adapter owns one exhaustive mapping from core errors to stable JavaScript errors.\n49: - Error messages and codes covered by TypeScript contracts are golden-tested.\n50: - Panic only for an impossible internal invariant, never for recoverable boundary input.\n51: \n52: ### Exhaustive Adapter Error Mapping\n53: \n54: ```rust\n55: #[derive(Debug)]\n56: struct JsErrorShape {\n57:     code: &'static str,\n58:     message: String,\n59: }\n60: \n61: fn map_ranking_error(error: RankingError) -> JsErrorShape {\n62:     match error {\n63:         RankingError::EmptyIdentifier => JsErrorShape {\n64:             code: \"INVALID_IDENTIFIER\",\n65:             message: error.to_string(),\n66:         },\n67:         RankingError::NonFiniteScore => JsErrorShape {\n68:             code: \"NON_FINITE_SCORE\",\n69:             message: error.to_string(),\n70:         },\n71:         RankingError::LimitExceeded { .. } => JsErrorShape {\n72:             code: \"LIMIT_EXCEEDED\",\n73:             message: error.to_string(),\n74:         },\n75:     }\n76: }\n77: ```\n78: \n79: The adapter must also preserve whether the existing TypeScript operation throws synchronously or rejects a Promise.\n80: \n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 321. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\ndescription: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n  - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n  - \"rust style guidance\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n\nFormatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n---\n\n### Error Style\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","text":"---\ntitle: Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\ndescription: Formatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment. — Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"rust typescript interop errors parity related resources\"\n  - \"rust interop errors and parity\"\n  - \"rust style guidance\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Rust/TypeScript Interop — Errors, Parity & Related Resources\n\nFormatting standards, naming conventions, and TypeScript interoperability rules for Rust files in the OpenCode development environment.\n\n---\n\n### Error Style\n\nCore public operations return domain-specific `Result` values backed by `thiserror`.\n\n```rust\nuse thiserror::Error;\n\n#[derive(Debug, Error)]\npub enum RankingError {\n    #[error(\"candidate identifier must not be empty\")]\n    EmptyIdentifier,\n\n    #[error(\"candidate score must be finite\")]\n    NonFiniteScore,\n\n    #[error(\"candidate limit {limit} exceeds maximum {maximum}\")]\n    LimitExceeded {\n        limit: u32,\n        maximum: u32,\n    },\n}\n```\n\nRules:\n\n- Core errors contain adapter-relevant structured context.\n- Core errors contain no napi-rs, WASM, or Node runtime types.\n- `anyhow` is prohibited in pure-core public APIs and exported functions.\n- `anyhow` MAY be used in sidecar `main`, build tooling, and the outermost non-ABI shell.\n- Every adapter owns one exhaustive mapping from core errors to stable JavaScript errors.\n- Error messages and codes covered by TypeScript contracts are golden-tested.\n- Panic only for an impossible internal invariant, never for recoverable boundary input.\n\n### Exhaustive Adapter Error Mapping\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug)]\nstruct JsErrorShape {\n    code: &'static str,\n    message: String,\n}\n\nfn map_ranking_error(error: RankingError) -> JsErrorShape {\n    match error {\n        RankingError::EmptyIdentifier => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"INVALID_IDENTIFIER\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n        RankingError::NonFiniteScore => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"NON_FINITE_SCORE\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n        RankingError::LimitExceeded { .. } => JsErrorShape {\n            code: \"LIMIT_EXCEEDED\",\n            message: error.to_string(),\n        },\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe adapter must also preserve whether the existing TypeScript operation throws synchronously or rejects a Promise.\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":80,"totalLines":321,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/rust/style_guide/interop_errors_and_parity.md","time":{"start":1783915761281,"end":1783915761293}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0022882c602ad73d016a5464f1267481918be1d9adf4d56fa8"}},"id":"prt_f59aa4e3f001ETCNYI5erlHNc5","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a9e074001szttQ6FV3B4V4D"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915761302,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_YaqjtQVifgNnaLUMriXihUiD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/patterns/tokens_state_machine_and_triggers.md","offset":1,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/patterns/tokens_state_machine_and_triggers.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\n3: description: Comprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow css patterns\"\n6:   - \"css state machines\"\n7:   - \"design token system webflow\"\n8:   - \"css validation architecture\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.4\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\n15: \n16: Comprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: This reference documents CSS patterns used in example.com's Webflow implementation. These patterns solve common challenges in Webflow projects: managing hover/focus states declaratively, handling form validation visually, ensuring accessibility compliance, and maintaining consistent design tokens.\n25: \n26: ### Prerequisites\n27: \n28: Follow code quality standards for all CSS implementations:\n29: - **Naming:** Use existing conventions documented in this file\n30: - **Accessibility:** Include `prefers-reduced-motion` for all animations\n31: - See [quality_standards.md](../quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) for complete requirements\n32: \n33: ### When to Use This Reference\n34: \n35: - Implementing hover/focus animations on cards or interactive elements\n36: - Building form validation with visual feedback\n37: - Ensuring keyboard vs mouse focus distinction\n38: - Working with Webflow Designer mode previews\n39: - Understanding the existing design token system\n40: \n41: ### Core Principle\n42: \n43: **Declarative CSS state management**: Use CSS custom properties as state signals (`--_state---on/off`) to drive animations, letting HTML data attributes determine behavior and CSS handle the visual response.\n44: \n45: ### Key Sources\n46: \n47: | Source File                                     | Pattern                  |\n48: | ----------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |\n49: | `/src/1_css/animations/hover_state_machine.css` | State machine pattern    |\n50: | `/src/1_css/form/form_validation.css`           | Validation states        |\n51: | `/src/1_css/form/input_main.css`                | Keyboard focus detection |\n52: | `/src/1_css/form/input_global.css`              | Mobile/browser fixes     |\n53: \n54: ---\n55: \n56: ## 2. WEBFLOW CSS TOKEN SYSTEM\n57: \n58: ### Important Disclaimer\n59: \n60: > **WEBFLOW-SPECIFIC**: The naming convention documented in this section (`--_category---subcategory--variant`) is specific to Webflow Designer's generated CSS. This is NOT a recommended general practice for CSS custom properties. This section documents how existing code works to ensure consistency when extending it - NOT as a template for new CSS projects outside Webflow.\n61: \n62: ### Token Naming Convention\n63: \n64: Webflow Designer generates CSS custom properties with a specific naming structure:\n65: \n66: ```\n67: --_category---subcategory--variant\n68: ```\n69: \n70: **Structure breakdown:**\n71: - `--_` - Prefix (underscore after double dash)\n72: - `category` - Top-level category (e.g., `color-tokens`, `layout`, `typography`)\n73: - `---` - Triple dash separator\n74: - `subcategory` - Specific token group (e.g., `input-bg`, `border-neutral`)\n75: - `--` - Double dash separator\n76: - `variant` - State or variation (e.g., `enabled`, `hover`, `primary`)\n77: \n78: ### Color Token Categories\n79: \n80: **Input tokens** (form elements):\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 449. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\ndescription: Comprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css patterns\"\n  - \"css state machines\"\n  - \"design token system webflow\"\n  - \"css validation architecture\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\n\nComprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/patterns/tokens_state_machine_and_triggers.md","text":"---\ntitle: CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\ndescription: Comprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow css patterns\"\n  - \"css state machines\"\n  - \"design token system webflow\"\n  - \"css validation architecture\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# CSS Patterns - Webflow Implementation Reference\n\nComprehensive CSS patterns for Webflow development including state machines, validation architecture, accessibility, and design token systems.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThis reference documents CSS patterns used in example.com's Webflow implementation. These patterns solve common challenges in Webflow projects: managing hover/focus states declaratively, handling form validation visually, ensuring accessibility compliance, and maintaining consistent design tokens.\n\n### Prerequisites\n\nFollow code quality standards for all CSS implementations:\n- **Naming:** Use existing conventions documented in this file\n- **Accessibility:** Include `prefers-reduced-motion` for all animations\n- See [quality_standards.md](../quality_standards/patterns_and_naming_enforcement.md) for complete requirements\n\n### When to Use This Reference\n\n- Implementing hover/focus animations on cards or interactive elements\n- Building form validation with visual feedback\n- Ensuring keyboard vs mouse focus distinction\n- Working with Webflow Designer mode previews\n- Understanding the existing design token system\n\n### Core Principle\n\n**Declarative CSS state management**: Use CSS custom properties as state signals (`--_state---on/off`) to drive animations, letting HTML data attributes determine behavior and CSS handle the visual response.\n\n### Key Sources\n\n| Source File                                     | Pattern                  |\n| ----------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ |\n| `/src/1_css/animations/hover_state_machine.css` | State machine pattern    |\n| `/src/1_css/form/form_validation.css`           | Validation states        |\n| `/src/1_css/form/input_main.css`                | Keyboard focus detection |\n| `/src/1_css/form/input_global.css`              | Mobile/browser fixes     |\n\n---\n\n## 2. WEBFLOW CSS TOKEN SYSTEM\n\n### Important Disclaimer\n\n> **WEBFLOW-SPECIFIC**: The naming convention documented in this section (`--_category---subcategory--variant`) is specific to Webflow Designer's generated CSS. This is NOT a recommended general practice for CSS custom properties. This section documents how existing code works to ensure consistency when extending it - NOT as a template for new CSS projects outside Webflow.\n\n### Token Naming Convention\n\nWebflow Designer generates CSS custom properties with a specific naming structure:\n\n```\n--_category---subcategory--variant\n```\n\n**Structure breakdown:**\n- `--_` - Prefix (underscore after double dash)\n- `category` - Top-level category (e.g., `color-tokens`, `layout`, `typography`)\n- `---` - Triple dash separator\n- `subcategory` - Specific token group (e.g., `input-bg`, `border-neutral`)\n- `--` - Double dash separator\n- `variant` - State or variation (e.g., `enabled`, `hover`, `primary`)\n\n### Color Token Categories\n\n**Input tokens** (form elements):","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":80,"totalLines":449,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/css/patterns/tokens_state_machine_and_triggers.md","time":{"start":1783915761285,"end":1783915761299}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0022882c602ad73d016a5464f127d481919915abe577bff8a7"}},"id":"prt_f59aa4e82001hP9qjlb820czSK","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a9e074001szttQ6FV3B4V4D"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915761333,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_HdO1FyASpEeW6kuzxvHsuPlL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md","offset":1,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Observer Patterns Reference\n3: description: Browser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow observer patterns\"\n6:   - \"mutationobserver cms content\"\n7:   - \"intersectionobserver visibility\"\n8:   - \"resizeobserver cleanup\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.4\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Observer Patterns Reference\n15: \n16: Browser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: Production-tested patterns for MutationObserver, IntersectionObserver, and ResizeObserver in Webflow projects with proper cleanup and performance optimization.\n24: \n25: ### When to Use (Observers vs Polling)\n26: \n27: | Approach | Use When | Performance |\n28: |----------|----------|-------------|\n29: | **MutationObserver** | Watching DOM changes (attributes, children, text) | Event-driven, efficient |\n30: | **IntersectionObserver** | Detecting element visibility/scroll position | Hardware-accelerated |\n31: | **Polling (setInterval)** | External state changes not reflected in DOM | Resource-intensive, avoid |\n32: | **ResizeObserver** | Tracking element size changes | Not currently used in codebase |\n33: \n34: **Rule of thumb:** If watching the DOM, use an observer. If watching non-DOM state, consider event listeners first.\n35: \n36: ---\n37: \n38: ## 2. MUTATIONOBSERVER\n39: \n40: ### When to Use\n41: \n42: - CMS content that loads dynamically after page render\n43: - Third-party widgets that modify the DOM\n44: - Attribute changes that trigger business logic (e.g., status indicators)\n45: - Webflow interactions that change data attributes\n46: \n47: ### Basic Pattern\n48: \n49: ```javascript\n50: /**\n51:  * Basic MutationObserver setup\n52:  * @param {Element} target - Element to observe\n53:  * @param {MutationCallback} callback - Handler for mutations\n54:  * @param {MutationObserverInit} options - Observer configuration\n55:  * @returns {Function} Cleanup function\n56:  */\n57: function observe_mutations(target, callback, options = {}) {\n58:   const observer = new MutationObserver(callback);\n59:   \n60:   observer.observe(target, {\n61:     attributes: true,\n62:     attributeFilter: [],    // Empty array = watch all attributes\n63:     childList: false,\n64:     subtree: false,\n65:     characterData: false,\n66:     ...options\n67:   });\n68:   \n69:   return () => observer.disconnect();\n70: }\n71: ```\n72: \n73: ### CMS Content Observation\n74: \n75: From `nav_notifications.js` - Watching office hours indicator for status changes:\n76: \n77: ```javascript\n78: /**\n79:  * Observe a status indicator element for attribute changes\n80:  * Used when CMS or external scripts update element state\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 379. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Observer Patterns Reference\ndescription: Browser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow observer patterns\"\n  - \"mutationobserver cms content\"\n  - \"intersectionobserver visibility\"\n  - \"resizeobserver cleanup\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Observer Patterns Reference\n\nBrowser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md","text":"---\ntitle: Observer Patterns Reference\ndescription: Browser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow observer patterns\"\n  - \"mutationobserver cms content\"\n  - \"intersectionobserver visibility\"\n  - \"resizeobserver cleanup\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Observer Patterns Reference\n\nBrowser observer APIs for reactive DOM watching, visibility detection, and scroll-triggered behaviors.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nProduction-tested patterns for MutationObserver, IntersectionObserver, and ResizeObserver in Webflow projects with proper cleanup and performance optimization.\n\n### When to Use (Observers vs Polling)\n\n| Approach | Use When | Performance |\n|----------|----------|-------------|\n| **MutationObserver** | Watching DOM changes (attributes, children, text) | Event-driven, efficient |\n| **IntersectionObserver** | Detecting element visibility/scroll position | Hardware-accelerated |\n| **Polling (setInterval)** | External state changes not reflected in DOM | Resource-intensive, avoid |\n| **ResizeObserver** | Tracking element size changes | Not currently used in codebase |\n\n**Rule of thumb:** If watching the DOM, use an observer. If watching non-DOM state, consider event listeners first.\n\n---\n\n## 2. MUTATIONOBSERVER\n\n### When to Use\n\n- CMS content that loads dynamically after page render\n- Third-party widgets that modify the DOM\n- Attribute changes that trigger business logic (e.g., status indicators)\n- Webflow interactions that change data attributes\n\n### Basic Pattern\n\n```javascript\n/**\n * Basic MutationObserver setup\n * @param {Element} target - Element to observe\n * @param {MutationCallback} callback - Handler for mutations\n * @param {MutationObserverInit} options - Observer configuration\n * @returns {Function} Cleanup function\n */\nfunction observe_mutations(target, callback, options = {}) {\n  const observer = new MutationObserver(callback);\n  \n  observer.observe(target, {\n    attributes: true,\n    attributeFilter: [],    // Empty array = watch all attributes\n    childList: false,\n    subtree: false,\n    characterData: false,\n    ...options\n  });\n  \n  return () => observer.disconnect();\n}\n```\n\n### CMS Content Observation\n\nFrom `nav_notifications.js` - Watching office hours indicator for status changes:\n\n```javascript\n/**\n * Observe a status indicator element for attribute changes\n * Used when CMS or external scripts update element state","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":80,"totalLines":379,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/observer_patterns/mutation_and_intersection.md","time":{"start":1783915761328,"end":1783915761332}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0022882c602ad73d016a5464f127e081918ed4cd5f8635ddd2"}},"id":"prt_f59aa4e86001WWfrIG32NFJl8l","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a9e074001szttQ6FV3B4V4D"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783915761557,"sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Fqw7yLvvqoC888NOkOqNVX0m","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/overview_hls_and_lenis.md","offset":1,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/overview_hls_and_lenis.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Third-Party Library Integrations\n3: description: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"webflow third party libraries\"\n6:   - \"hls js video streaming\"\n7:   - \"external library integration\"\n8:   - \"library loading pattern webflow\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 3.5.0.4\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Third-Party Library Integrations\n15: \n16: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns following code quality standards.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects.\n24: \n25: ### When to Use\n26: - Integrating new third-party libraries\n27: - Managing dependencies (CDN, versions)\n28: - Handling external script loading\n29: \n30: ### Integration Principles\n31: \n32: 1. **CDN-first loading** - Use jsDelivr or unpkg for reliable delivery\n33: 2. **Version pinning** - Always pin to specific versions for stability\n34: 3. **Feature detection** - Check library availability before use\n35: 4. **Graceful fallbacks** - Handle missing/failed libraries gracefully\n36: 5. **Memory management** - Proper cleanup to prevent leaks\n37: \n38: ### Loading Pattern\n39: \n40: ```javascript\n41: const LIBRARY_CDN_URL = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library@{version}';\n42: \n43: async function load_library() {\n44:   if (typeof window.Library !== 'undefined') {\n45:     return true;\n46:   }\n47: \n48:   return new Promise((resolve) => {\n49:     const script = document.createElement('script');\n50:     script.src = LIBRARY_CDN_URL;\n51:     script.async = true;\n52:     script.onload = () => resolve(true);\n53:     script.onerror = () => resolve(false);\n54:     document.head.appendChild(script);\n55:   });\n56: }\n57: ```\n58: \n59: ---\n60: \n61: ## 2. HLS.JS (VIDEO STREAMING)\n62: \n63: HTTP Live Streaming library for adaptive video playback in non-Safari browsers.\n64: \n65: ### CDN URL\n66: \n67: ```html\n68: <!-- Preload for critical video pages -->\n69: <link rel=\"preload\" href=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{version}\" as=\"script\">\n70: \n71: <!-- Load with defer -->\n72: <script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{version}\" defer></script>\n73: ```\n74: \n75: ### Feature Detection\n76: \n77: ```javascript\n78: const test_video = document.createElement('video');\n79: const safari_native = !!test_video.canPlayType('application/vnd.apple.mpegurl');\n80: const can_use_hls_js = !!(window.Hls && Hls.isSupported()) && !safari_native;\n\n(Showing lines 1-80 of 214. Use offset=81 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Third-Party Library Integrations\ndescription: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow third party libraries\"\n  - \"hls js video streaming\"\n  - \"external library integration\"\n  - \"library loading pattern webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Third-Party Library Integrations\n\nReference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns following code quality standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/overview_hls_and_lenis.md","text":"---\ntitle: Third-Party Library Integrations\ndescription: Reference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"webflow third party libraries\"\n  - \"hls js video streaming\"\n  - \"external library integration\"\n  - \"library loading pattern webflow\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 3.5.0.4\n---\n\n# Third-Party Library Integrations\n\nReference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects, with production-tested patterns following code quality standards.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\nReference guide for integrating external JavaScript libraries in Webflow projects.\n\n### When to Use\n- Integrating new third-party libraries\n- Managing dependencies (CDN, versions)\n- Handling external script loading\n\n### Integration Principles\n\n1. **CDN-first loading** - Use jsDelivr or unpkg for reliable delivery\n2. **Version pinning** - Always pin to specific versions for stability\n3. **Feature detection** - Check library availability before use\n4. **Graceful fallbacks** - Handle missing/failed libraries gracefully\n5. **Memory management** - Proper cleanup to prevent leaks\n\n### Loading Pattern\n\n```javascript\nconst LIBRARY_CDN_URL = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/library@{version}';\n\nasync function load_library() {\n  if (typeof window.Library !== 'undefined') {\n    return true;\n  }\n\n  return new Promise((resolve) => {\n    const script = document.createElement('script');\n    script.src = LIBRARY_CDN_URL;\n    script.async = true;\n    script.onload = () => resolve(true);\n    script.onerror = () => resolve(false);\n    document.head.appendChild(script);\n  });\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. HLS.JS (VIDEO STREAMING)\n\nHTTP Live Streaming library for adaptive video playback in non-Safari browsers.\n\n### CDN URL\n\n```html\n<!-- Preload for critical video pages -->\n<link rel=\"preload\" href=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{version}\" as=\"script\">\n\n<!-- Load with defer -->\n<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/hls.js@{version}\" defer></script>\n```\n\n### Feature Detection\n\n```javascript\nconst test_video = document.createElement('video');\nconst safari_native = !!test_video.canPlayType('application/vnd.apple.mpegurl');\nconst can_use_hls_js = !!(window.Hls && Hls.isSupported()) && !safari_native;","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":80,"totalLines":214,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/third_party_integrations/overview_hls_and_lenis.md","time":{"start":1783915761528,"end":1783915761556}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0022882c602ad73d016a5464f127e88191a5184ac98af9fe72"}},"id":"prt_f59aa4ec5001FkciBZZy7V9ZKz","sessionID":"ses_0a65ac46dffebja9CFmlcvrGJ0","messageID":"msg_f59a9e074001szttQ6FV3B4V4D"}}
